<!-- The paragraph below was created by consensus after considerable discussion by a variety of editors. Out of courtesy for this process, please discuss any proposed changes on the talk page before editing it. -->
'''Jesus''' ({{IPAc-en|icon|<U+02C8>|d<U+0292>|i<U+02D0>|z|<U+0259>|s}}; {{lang-grc-gre|<U+1F38><U+03B7><U+03C3><U+03BF><U+1FE6><U+03C2>|I<U+0113>sous}}; 7<U+2013>2 BC/BCE to 30<U+2013>36 AD/CE), also referred to as '''Jesus of Nazareth''', is the central figure of [[Christianity]], whom the teachings of most [[Christian denominations]]<!-- NOTE: "most" makes a required distinction in that Christianity is diverse, and not all are Trinitarian or Nicene-based --> hold to be the [[Son of God]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Placher|first=William C.|title=Readings in the History of Christian Theology|year=1988|isbn=0-664-24057-7|pages=52<U+2013>53|postscript=. The first sentence of the Gospel of Mark ([[s:Bible (American Standard)/Mark#1:1|Mk 1:1]]) includes Son of God and the term is also part of the [[Nicene Creed]], the most widely used Christian creed.}}</ref> Christians hold Jesus to be the awaited [[Messiah]] of the [[Old Testament]] and refer to him as '''Jesus Christ''' or simply [[Christ]],<ref>{{harvnb|Brown|1977|p=9}}
* {{cite book |last=Strobel |first=Lee |year=2007 |title= The case for the real Jesus: a journalist investigates current attacks on the identity of Christ |page=200 |location=Grand Rapids, MI |publisher=Zondervan |isbn=978-0-310-24061-7}}</ref> a name that is also used by non-Christians. Jesus is also considered to be a [[Prophets in Islam|prophet in]] [[Islam]].

<!-- The paragraph below was created by consensus after considerable discussion by a variety of editors. Out of courtesy for this process, please discuss any proposed changes on the talk page before editing it. -->
<!--
READ THIS FIRST.
The following references are WP:RS sources which are used per WP:RS/AC guideline.
The issue has been discussed on the talk page at length
See the "talk page FAQ" about it - it may answer your question..

The main source says "scholars of antiquity", other sources say "scholars", "biblical scholars and classical historians"  and "historians".

Sources do not say "X scholars" or "Christian scholars", so do not modify it as such
for that will make it deviate from what the sources state.
The source says "virtually all", so do NOT change it to "most", "several", "many", etc.
-->
Virtually all modern scholars of antiquity agree that a [[Historicity of Jesus|historical Jesus existed]],<ref name=Existence>In a 2011 review of the state of modern scholarship, [[Bart Ehrman]] (who is a secular agnostic) wrote: "He certainly existed, as virtually every competent scholar of antiquity, Christian or non-Christian, agrees" ({{harvnb|Ehrman|2011|p=285}}).
* [[Richard A. Burridge]] states: "There are those who argue that Jesus is a figment of the Church's imagination, that there never was a Jesus at all. I have to say that I do not know any respectable critical scholar who says that any more" ({{harvnb|Burridge|Gould|2004|p=34}}).
* [[Robert M. Price]] (an atheist who denies existence) agrees that this perspective runs against the views of the majority of scholars ({{harvnb|Price|2009|p=61}}).
* James D. G. Dunn states that the theories of non-existence of Jesus are "a thoroughly dead thesis" ({{harvnb|Sykes|2007|pp=35<U+2013>36}}).
* [[Michael Grant (author)|Michael Grant]] (a [[classicist]]) states that "In recent years, 'no serious scholar has ventured to postulate the non historicity of Jesus' or at any rate very few, and they have not succeeded in disposing of the much stronger, indeed very abundant, evidence to the contrary" ({{harvnb|Grant|1977|p=200}}).
* [[Robert E. Van Voorst]] states that biblical scholars and classical historians regard theories of non-existence of Jesus as effectively refuted ({{harvnb|Van Voorst|2000|p=16}}).<!--Note that this is a different statement with a different qualifier from the existence statement--></ref> although [[quest for the historical Jesus|there is little agreement]] on the [[Historical reliability of the Gospels|reliability of the gospel narratives]] and their theological assertions of his divinity.<ref name=HistJesus>{{cite journal|first=Craig |last=Evans |title=Life-of-Jesus Research and the Eclipse of Mythology| journal= Theological Studies | volume= 54 |year= 1993 | page= 5 |url=http://www.apologeticsinthechurch.com/uploads/7/4/5/6/7456646/mythology_and_jesus.pdf}}
* {{cite book| first=Charles H.| last= Talbert| title= What Is a Gospel? The Genre of Canonical Gospels | page= 42 |location= Philadelphia |publisher= Fortress Press |year= 1977}}
* {{harvnb|Sanders|1993|p=3.}}
* {{harvnb|Powell|1998|pp=168<U+2013>173}}</ref> Most scholars agree that Jesus was a [[Jewish]] teacher from [[Galilee]], [[Baptism of Jesus|was baptized]] by [[John the Baptist]], and [[Crucifixion of Jesus|was crucified]] in [[Jerusalem]] on the orders of the [[Roman governor|Roman prefect]], [[Pontius Pilate]].{{sfnm|Brown|1994|1p=964|2a1=Carson|2a2=Moo|2a3=Morris|1992|2pp=50-56|Crossan|1993|3pp=xi-xiii|Fredriksen|1999|4pp=6-7, 105-110, 232-234, 266|Maier|1991|5pp=1, 99, 121, 171|Meier|1991|6pp=68, 146, 199, 278, 386}}{{sfnm|Dunn|2003|1p=339|Meier|1994|2pp=12-13|Vermes|1973|3p=37|Wright|1998|4pp=32, 83, 100<U+2013>102, 222|Witherington|1998|5pp=12-20}} Scholars have offered various portraits of the [[historical Jesus]], which at times share a number of overlapping attributes, such as the leader of an [[apocalypticism|apocalyptic]] movement, Messiah, a charismatic healer, a sage and philosopher, or a [[social reform]]er who preached of the "[[Kingdom of God (Christianity)|Kingdom of God]]" as a means for personal and [[egalitarianism|egalitarian]] social transformation.{{sfnm|1a1=Fredriksen|2000|1pp={{nowrap|6<U+2013>7, 105<U+2013>110, 232<U+2013>234, 266}}|2a1=Theissen|1998|2pp=1-16|3a1=Dunn|2003|3pp=47-49|4a1=K<U+00F6>stenberger |4a2=Kellum|4a3=Quarles|2009|4pp=117<U+2013>125}}<ref>For further information, see the [[Jesus#Portraits of Jesus|Portraits of Jesus]] section.</ref> Scholars have correlated the [[New Testament]] accounts with non-Christian historical records to arrive at an estimated [[Chronology of Jesus|chronology of Jesus' life]].{{sfnm|1a1=K<U+00F6>stenberger|1a2=Kellum|1a3=Quarles|1y=2009|1p=114|2a1=Maier|2y=1989|2pp=113-129|3a1=Van Voorst|3y2000|3pp=39-42|4a1=Niswonger|4y=1992|4pp=121-124}}<ref>The methodology for constructing the historical portraits has been criticized by [[Donald Akenson|Akenson]] (Akenson 1998, pp. 539<U+2013>555).</ref>

Most Christians believe that Jesus was conceived by the [[Holy Spirit (Christianity)|Holy Spirit]], [[Virgin birth of Jesus|born of a virgin]], performed [[Miracles of Jesus|miracles]], founded [[Christian Church|the Church]], died sacrificially [[Crucifixion of Jesus|by crucifixion]] to achieve [[Atonement in Christianity|atonement]], [[Resurrection of Jesus|rose from the dead]], and [[Ascension of Jesus|ascended]] into [[Heaven (Christianity)|heaven]], from which he [[Second Coming|will return]].{{sfn|Grudem|1994|pp=568-603}} The majority of Christians worship Jesus as the incarnation of [[God the Son]], who is the Second Person of the [[Trinity|Holy Trinity]].<ref name="NWTrin">{{cite encyclopedia|url=http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/15047a.htm|title=The dogma of the Trinity|encyclopedia=Catholic Encyclopedia|editor=Kevin Knight|publisher=New Advent|accessdate=2013-04-14}}
</ref> A few Christian groups [[Nontrinitarianism|reject Trinitarianism]], wholly or partly, as non-scriptural.<ref name="NWTrin" /><ref>{{cite encyclopedia|title=Antitrinitarianism| url=http://www.gameo.org/encyclopedia/contents/A597.html| last=Friedmann|first=Robert|year=1953| encyclopedia=Global Anabaptist Mennonite Encyclopedia Online|accessdate=2012-10-24}}</ref>

In [[Jesus in Islam|Islam]], Jesus (commonly transliterated as {{transl|ar|ISO|[[Isa (name)|Isa]]}}) is considered one of [[God in Islam|God's]] important [[Prophets of Islam|prophets]].{{sfnm|Houlden|2006|1p=184|D<U+00FC>zg<U+00FC>n|2004|2p=20}} To Muslims, Jesus is a bringer of [[Injil|scripture]], and the product of a virgin birth, but not the victim of crucifixion. Judaism [[Jewish views of Jesus|rejects]] the belief that Jesus was the awaited Messiah, arguing that he did not fulfill the [[Jewish messiah|Messianic prophecies]] in the [[Tanakh]].<ref>{{cite book |first=Asher |last=Norman |title= Twenty-six reasons why Jews don't believe in Jesus |url=http://books.google.com/?id=tx5qrKz6dRMC&pg=PR17&dq=Judaism+rejects+assertions+that+Jesus+was+the+awaited+Messiah,+arguing+that+he+did+not+fulfill+the&q |publisher= Feldheim Publishers |location= Nanuet, NY |year=2007 |pages=16<U+2013>18, 89<U+2013>96 |isbn=978-0-9771937-0-7}}</ref> [[Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED>]] scripture almost never refers to Jesus as the Messiah, but calls him a [[Manifestation of God]].<ref name="manifestation">{{cite journal | first = Juan | last = Cole | title = The Concept of Manifestation in the Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED> Writings| year = 1982 | journal = Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED> Studies | volume = monograph 9  | pages = 1<U+2013>38 | url = http://bahai-library.com/cole_concept_manifestation}}</ref>{{TOC limit|3}}

== Etymology of names ==
{{further|Jesus (name)|Holy Name of Jesus|Name of God in Christianity|Yeshua (name)}}

In the [[Christian biblical canons|Christian Bible]], Jesus is referred to as "Jesus from Nazareth" ([[s:Bible (American Standard)/Matthew#21:11|Matthew 21:11]]), "Joseph's son" ([[s:Bible (American Standard)/Luke#4:12|Luke 4:12]]), and "Jesus son of Joseph from Nazareth" ([[s:Bible (American Standard)/John#1:45|John 1:45]]). Paul the Apostle most often referred to Jesus as "Jesus Christ", "Christ Jesus", or "Christ".<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|title=Saint Paul, the Apostle|encyclopedia= Encyclop<U+00E6>dia Britannica|publisher= Encyclop<U+00E6>dia Britannica Inc.|accessdate=2013-04-14 |url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/447019/Saint-Paul-the-Apostle}}</ref> In the [[Quran]], the central religious text of Islam, he is referred to as {{rtl-lang|ar|<U+0639><U+064A><U+0633><U+0649>}} (<U+2018><U+012A>sa).<ref>{{cite book|authorlink=Brown Driver Briggs|first=Brown Driver|last=Briggs|title=Hebrew and English Lexicon|publisher=Hendrickson Publishers|year=1996|isbn=1-56563-206-0}}</ref>{{sfn|Liddell|Scott|1889|p=824}}

"Jesus" is a Latin [[transliteration]], occurring in a number of languages and based on the [[Greek language|Greek]] {{lang|grc|<U+1F38><U+03B7><U+03C3><U+03BF><U+1FE6><U+03C2>}} (''{{lang|grc-Latn|I<U+0113>so<U+00FB>s}}'').<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/08374x.htm | title=The Name of Jesus Christ | publisher=Catholic Encyclopedia | accessdate=2013-04-22}}</ref> The Greek form is a [[hellenization]] of the [[Aramaic language|Aramaic]]/[[Hebrew language|Hebrew]] {{rtl-lang|arc|<U+05D9><U+05E9><U+05D5><U+05E2>}} (''Y<U+0113><U+0161><U+016B><U+0103><U+2018>'') which is a [[Second Temple Judaism#Return from Babylonian captivity|post-Exilic]] modification of the Hebrew {{rtl-lang|he|<U+05D9><U+05B0><U+05D4><U+05D5><U+05B9><U+05E9><U+05BB><U+05C1><U+05E2><U+05B7>}} (''Y<U+0115>h<U+014D><U+0161>u<U+0103><U+2018>'', [[Joshua]]) under influence from Aramaic.<ref name=Perkins>{{cite journal | title=What's in a Name&nbsp;<U+2013> Proper Names in Greek Exodus | author=Perkins, Larry | journal=Journal for the Study of Judaism | year=2010 | volume=41 | issue=4<U+2013>5 | page=454 | doi=10.1163/157006310X503630}}</ref> The etymology of the name Jesus in the context of the New Testament is generally expressed as "[[Yahweh]] saves"<ref>{{cite book| first=Larry W. |last=Hurtado|year= 2005 |title=Lord Jesus Christ: Devotion to Jesus in Earliest Christianity| isbn=978-0-8028-3167-5 |page= 392}}
* {{harvnb|Green|1997|p=88}}
* {{cite book| title=Reading Matthew: a literary and theological commentary |first=David E. |last= Garland |year=1999 |isbn=1-57312-274-2 |page=23}}</ref> or "Yahweh is salvation".<ref>{{cite book|title=The Gospel of Matthew|first= by R. T. |last= France |year= 2007 | isbn=0-8028-2501-X |page=78}}
* Davies & Allison 2004, p. 155</ref> The name Jesus appears to have been in use in Judea at the time of the birth of Jesus.<ref>{{cite book|title=Matthew |first=Douglas |last=Hare |year=2009 |isbn=0-664-23433-X |page=11}}</ref> The first century works of historian [[Flavius Josephus]] refer to at least twenty different people with the name Jesus.{{sfn|Eddy|Boyd|2007|p=129}} [[Philo]]'s reference in ''[[Mutatione Nominum]]'' item 121 indicates that the etymology of the name Joshua was known outside Judea at the time.{{sfn|Davies|Allison|2004|p=209}}

"[[Christ]]" ({{IPAc-en|icon|<U+02C8>|k|r|a<U+026A>|s|t}}) is derived from the Greek {{lang|grc|<U+03A7><U+03C1><U+03B9><U+03C3><U+03C4><U+03CC><U+03C2>}} (''Khr<U+012B>stos''), meaning "[[anointing|the anointed]]" or "the anointed one", a translation of the Hebrew {{lang| he| <U+05DE><U+05B8><U+05E9><U+05B4><U+05C1><U+05D9><U+05D7><U+05B7>}} (''{{unicode|M<U+0101><U+0161><U+00EE>a<U+1E25>}}''), usually transliterated into [[English language|English]] as "[[Messiah]]" ({{IPAc-en|icon|m|<U+0268>|<U+02C8>|s|a<U+026A>|.|<U+0259>}}).<ref name="Vine1940">{{cite book|title= [[Vine's Expository Dictionary|Expository Dictionary of New Testament Words]]|last= Vine | first= WE |authorlink= William Edwy Vine|year= 1940|publisher= Fleming H. Revell Company|location= Old Tappan, NJ |pages=274<U+2013>275}}</ref> In the [[Septuagint]] version of the [[Hebrew Bible]] (written well over a century before the time of Jesus), the word "Christ" ({{lang|grc|<U+03A7><U+03C1><U+03B9><U+03C3><U+03C4><U+03CC><U+03C2>}}) was used to translate the Hebrew word "Messiah" ({{lang|he|<U+05DE><U+05B8><U+05E9><U+05B4><U+05C1><U+05D9><U+05D7><U+05B7>}}) into Greek.{{sfn|Zanzig|2000|p=314}} In [[s:Bible (American Standard)/Matthew#16:16|Matthew 16:16]], the apostle [[Saint Peter|Peter]]'s profession "You are the Christ" identifies Jesus as the Messiah.<ref>{{cite book|title=Christianity|first=Donald W.|last= Ekstrand |year= 2008| isbn= 1-60477-929-2 |pages= 147<U+2013>150}}</ref> In postbiblical usage, "Christ" became viewed as a name, one part of "Jesus Christ", but originally it was a title ("Jesus the Anointed").<ref>{{harvnb|Pannenberg|1968|pp=30<U+2013>31}}
* {{harvnb|Doninger|1999|p=212}}
* {{cite book|title=Theology of the New Testament| first=Rudolf K.|last= Bultmann |year=2007 |isbn= 1-932792-93-7 |page= 80}}</ref>

== Chronology ==
{{Main|Chronology of Jesus}}
[[File:Palestine in the time of Jesus.jpg|thumb|right|[[Judea]] and [[Galilee]] at the time of Jesus.]]

Most scholars agree that Jesus was a [[Galilee|Galilean]] [[Jew]] who was born around the beginning of the first century and died 30<U+2013>36 AD/CE in [[Judea]].{{sfnm|Maier|1989|1pp=113-129|K<U+00F6>stenberger|Kellum|Quarles|2009|2p=114}} [[Amy-Jill Levine]] states that the general scholarly consensus is that Jesus was a contemporary of [[John the Baptist]] and was crucified by Roman governor [[Pontius Pilate]] who reigned 26<U+2013>36 AD/CE.{{sfn|Levine|2006|p=4|ps=: "There is a consensus of sorts on the basic outline of Jesus' life in that most scholars agree that Jesus was baptized by [[John the Baptist]], debated Jewish authorities on the subject of God, performed some healings, gathered followers, and was crucified by Roman prefect [[Pontius Pilate]] who reigned 26<U+2013>36 AD"}} Most scholars hold that Jesus lived in Galilee and Judea, and did not preach or study elsewhere.<ref name=KGreen442>{{cite book|first1=Joel B. |last1=Green |first2=Scot |last2=McKnight |first3= I. Howard |last3=Marshall|title= Dictionary of Jesus and the Gospels |url=http://books.google.com/books?id=9ntwNm-tOogC&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false |publisher=InterVarsity Press| year=1992 | page=442}}</ref><ref name=Dunn303>{{cite encyclopedia|title=The Spirit-Filled Experience of Jesus|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=37uJRUF6btAC&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q=%22We%20may%20surmise%20that%20he%22&f=false|first=Marcus J. |last=Borg |encyclopedia=The Historical Jesus in Recent Research|editor-first1=James D. G.|editor-last1= Dunn |editor-first2=Scot |editor-last2=McKnight|year= 2006 |isbn= 1-57506-100-7 |page= 303}}</ref>{{sfn|Crossan|Watts|1999|pp=28-29}}

The general scholarly agreement on the [[historicity]] of the interaction of Jesus with John the Baptist and Pontius Pilate shapes the approximate chronological picture. In the ''[[Antiquities of the Jews]]'', first century historian [[Flavius Josephus|Josephus]] [[s:The Antiquities of the Jews/Book XVIII#Chapter 5|places the execution]] of the Baptist before the defeat of [[Herod Antipas]] by [[Aretas IV Philopatris|Aretas IV]] which took place in 36 AD/CE;<ref name=Evans&Gillman>{{cite encyclopedia|first=Craig |last=Evans|year= 2006| url=http://books.google.com/books?id=wMbEyeDSQQgC&pg=PA55#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=Josephus on John the Baptist| encyclopedia=The Historical Jesus in Context| editor-first1=Amy-Jill |editor-last1=Levine| editor-first2=Dale C.|editor-last2=Allison|editor-first3=John D.|editor-last3=Crossan|publisher=Princeton Univ Press| isbn= 978-0-691-00992-6 |pages=55<U+2013>58}}
*{{cite book|title=Herodias: at home in that fox's den|first= Florence M.|last= Gillman |year=2003| isbn= 0-8146-5108-9| pages=25<U+2013>30}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Herod Antipas| first=Harold W. |last=Hoehner |year=1983 |isbn= 0-310-42251-5| page= 131|postscript=. In his analysis of [[Herod Antipas]]'s life, [[Harold Hoehner]] estimates that John the Baptist's imprisonment by Herod probably occurred around AD/CE 30-31.}}</ref> and the dates for the reign of Pontius Pilate are well established by Roman sources.{{sfnm|Houlden|2003|1pp=508-509|Carter|2003|2pp=44-45}}

Two independent approaches have been used to estimate the year of the birth of Jesus; one combines the [[Nativity of Jesus|Nativity]] accounts in the Gospels with other historical data, the other works backwards from the estimation of the start of the [[ministry of Jesus|his ministry]].{{sfnm|1a1=Maier|1y=1989|1pp=113-129|2a1=Niswonger|2y=1992|2pp=121-124}} The first approach uses [[s:Bible (American Standard)/Matthew#2:1|Matthew 2:1]]'s association of the birth of Jesus with the reign of [[Herod the Great]], who died around 4 BC/BCE and [[s:Bible (American Standard)/Luke#1:5|Luke 1:5]]'s mention of the reign of Herod shortly before the birth of Jesus.{{sfnm|Niswonger|1992|1pp=121-124|Rahner|2004|2pp=730-731|Niswonger|1992|3pp=121-124}} However, Luke's gospel also associates the birth with the [[Census of Quirinius|first census]], which was in 6 AD/CE.{{sfn|Vermes|2006|p=22}} The second approach ignores the Nativity accounts, and correlates  [[s:Bible (American Standard)/John#2:13|John 2:13<U+2013>20]]'s statement about the [[Jerusalem Temple]] being in its 46th year of construction, with [[Josephus]]' dating of the death of [[John the Baptist]] to work backwards from the statement in [[s:Bible (American Standard)/Luke#3:23|Luke 3:23]] that Jesus was "about 30 years of age" at the start of his ministry.{{sfnm|K<U+00F6>stenberger|Kellum|Quarles|2009|1p=140|Maier|1989|2pp=113-129}} This approach indicates that around 27<U+2013>29 AD/CE, Jesus was "about thirty years of age".<ref name=Scarola /> Elsewhere, [[s:Bible (American Standard)/John#8:57|John 8:57]] states that Jesus was less than fifty years old. Some scholars thus estimate the year 28 AD/CE to be roughly the 32nd birthday of Jesus.{{sfnm|1a1=K<U+00F6>stenberger |1a2=Kellum |1a3=Quarles |2009|1p=140|Maier|1989|2pp=113-129}}<ref name=Novak302>{{cite book|title=Christianity and the Roman Empire: background texts|first=Ralph M. |last=Novak |year=2001 |isbn= 1-56338-347-0 |pages= 302<U+2013>303}}</ref> Most scholars assume a date of birth between 6 and 4 BC/BCE,{{sfn|Dunn|2003|p=324}} but some say it's between 7 and 2 BC/BCE.{{sfnm|1a1=Carson|1a2=Moo|1a3=Morris|1y=1992|1pp={{nowrap|54, 56}}|2a1=Grant|2y=1977|2p=71|3a1=Meier|3y=1991|3p=214|4a1=Sanders|4y=1993|4pp=10-11|5a1=Witherington|5y=1998|5loc=No. 3:12<U+2013>20|ps={{sp}}are some of the historians and Biblical scholars who place the birth and death of Jesus within this range.}}

[[File:Jerus-n4i.jpg|thumb|left|[[Israel Museum]] model of [[Herod's Temple]], referred to in [[s:Bible (American Standard)/John#2:13|John 2:13]].]]
The years of [[ministry of Jesus]] have been estimated with three different approaches.{{sfn|K<U+00F6>stenberger |Kellum|Quarles|2009|p=140}}<ref name=Scarola >{{cite encyclopedia|first=Jack V.|last= Scarola|title= A Chronology of the nativity Era| encyclopedia=Chronos, kairos, Christos 2|editor-first1=Ray|editor-last1= Summers|editor-first2= Jerry |editor-last2=Vardaman|year= 1998 |isbn= 0-86554-582-0 |pages= 61<U+2013>81}}
*{{harvnb|Freedman|2000|p=249}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Luke 1<U+2013>5: New Testament Commentary|first= John |last=MacArthur |year=2009 |isbn =978-0-8024-0871-6 |page= 201}}</ref> The first approach uses the dates for [[Tiberius]]' reign and combines them with [[wikisource:Bible (American Standard)/Luke#3:1|Luke 3:1<U+2013>2]]'s reference to its 15th year as the start of the ministry of [[John the Baptist]] and [[wikisource:Bible (American Standard)/Acts#10:37|Acts 10:37<U+2013>38]]'s reference to John's ministry preceding that of Jesus to arrive at a date around 28<U+2013>29 AD/CE.{{sfn|Maier|1989|pp=113-129}}<ref name=Scarola /><ref name=Tempvisit>{{cite book|title=The Riddles of the Fourth Gospel: An Introduction to John|first= Paul N. |last=Anderson |year=2011 |isbn= 0-8006-0427-X |page= 200|postscript=. Anderson dates the temple incident at "around 26<U+2013>27 AD/CE".}}
* {{cite book|title=Herod the Great|first=Jerry |last=Knoblet |year=2005 |isbn= 0-7618-3087-1 |page= 184|postscript=. Jerry Knoblet estimates the date as around 27 AD/CE.}}
* Freedman states that Jesus began his ministry "ca 28 AD" at "ca age 31" ({{harvnb|Freedman|2000|p=249}}).
* Paul L. Maier specifically states that he considers the Temple visit date in John at "around 29 AD/CE", using various factors that he summarizes in a chronology table. Maier's table considers 28 AD/CE to be roughly the 32nd birthday of Jesus and 5 BC/BCE to be the year of birth of Jesus {{harv|Maier|1989|pp=113<U+2013>129}}.
* K<U+00F6>stenberger, Kellum and Quarles make the same statement as Maier, namely that the 32nd birthday of Jesus was around 28 AD/CE when his ministry began ({{harvnb|K<U+00F6>stenberger|Kellum|Quarles|2009|p=114}}).
* {{cite book|title=Jesus in Johannine tradition|first1=Robert T. |last1=Fortna| first2=Tom |last2=Thatcher |year=2001 |isbn= 978-0-664-22219-2 |page= 77|postscript=. In their book, Robert Fortna and Thatcher estimate the date at around 28 AD/CE.}}</ref> The second approach uses [[s:Bible (American Standard)/John#2:13|John 2:13<U+2013>20]]'s statement about the Temple, [[wikisource:The Antiquities of the Jews/Book XV|Josephus' statement]] that the temple's reconstruction was started by Herod in the 18th year of his reign to estimate a date around 27<U+2013>29 AD/CE.{{sfnm|1a1=K<U+00F6>stenberger|1a2=Kellum|1a3=Quarles|1y=2009|1p=114|2a1=Maier|2y=1989|2pp=113-129|3a1=Van Voorst|3y2000|3pp=39-42|4a1=Niswonger|4y=1992|4pp=121-124}} A third method uses the date of the [[death of John the Baptist]] and the marriage of [[Herod Antipas]] to [[Herodias]] based on the writings of Josephus, and correlates it with [[s:Bible (American Standard)/Matthew#14:4|Matthew 14:4]] and [[wikisource:Bible (American Standard)/Mark#6:18|Mark 6:18]].<ref name=Evans&Gillman/> Given that most scholars date the marriage of Herod and Herodias as AD/CE 28<U+2013>35 this yields a date about 28<U+2013>29 AD/CE.{{sfn|K<U+00F6>stenberger |Kellum|Quarles|2009|p=140}}{{sfn|Freedman|2000|p=249}}<ref name="Novak302"/><ref>{{cite book|title = Chronological Aspects of the Life of Christ |last = Hoehner|first = Harold W |authorlink = Harold Hoehner|year= 1978|publisher=Zondervan |isbn= 0-310-26211-9|pages= 29<U+2013>37|url = http://books.google.com/?id=6z-NcR7fVSIC&dq=CHronological+Aspects+of+the+Life+of+Christ}}
* Luke states that John's ministry began in the fifteenth year of the reign of [[Tiberius|Tiberius Caesar]], when [[Pontius Pilate]] was the Roman governor of Judaea, and [[Herod Antipas]] was [[tetrarchy (Judea)|tetrarch]] of [[Galilee]], and his brother Philip was tetrarch of the region of [[Iturea]] and [[Trachonitis]], and [[Lysanias]] was tetrarch of [[Abilene (biblical)|Abilene]], during the [[List of High Priests of Israel|high priesthood]] of [[Annas]] and [[Caiaphas]].</ref>

A number of approaches have been used to estimate the date of the crucifixion of Jesus, scholars generally agreeing that he died between 30<U+2013>36 AD/CE.{{sfnm|1a1=K<U+00F6>stenberger|1a2=Kellum|1a3=Quarles|1y=2009|1p=114|2a1=Barnett|2y=2002|2pp=19-21|3a1=Maier|3y=1989 |3pp=113-129|4a1=Sanders|4y=1993|4p=54|5a1=Vermes|5y=2004|5p=371}} One approach relies on the dates of the prefecture of [[Pontius Pilate]] who was the Roman governor of Judea from 26 AD/CE until 36 AD/CE, after which he was replaced by [[Marcellus (prefect of Judea)|Marcellus]], 36<U+2013>37 AD.{{sfn|Theissen|Merz|1998|pp=81-83}}{{sfn|Green|1997|p=168}}{{sfn|Carter|2003|pp=44<U+2013>45}} Another approach which provides an [[upper bound]] for the year of death of Jesus is working backwards from the chronology of [[Apostle Paul]], which can be historically pegged to his trial in [[Achaea]], Greece, by Roman [[proconsul]] [[Lucius Junius Gallio Annaeanus|Gallio]], the date of whose reign is confirmed in the [[Delphi Inscription]] discovered in the 20th century at the [[Temple of Apollo (Delphi)|Temple of Apollo]].{{sfn|Barnett|2002|p=19-21}}{{sfn|K<U+00F6>stenberger|Kellum|Quarles|2009|pp=77-79}} The estimation of the date of the [[Conversion of Paul the Apostle|conversion of Paul]] places the death of Jesus before this conversion, which is estimated at around 33<U+2013>36 AD/CE.{{sfn|Barnett|2002|p=19-21}}{{sfn|K<U+00F6>stenberger|Kellum|Quarles|2009|pp=77-79}}<ref name=Riesner >{{cite book|title=Paul's early period: chronology, mission strategy, theology|authorlink=Rainer Riesner|last=Riesner|first=Rainer|year= 1997 |isbn= 978-0-8028-4166-7| pages= 19<U+2013>27}}</ref> [[Isaac Newton]] was one of the first astronomers to [[s:Observations_upon_the_Prophecies_of_Daniel/Part_I_Chap_XI|estimate the date]] of the crucifixion and suggested Friday, April 3, 34 AD/CE.<ref name=Pratt /><ref>{{cite book|authorlink=Isaac Newton|last=Newton|first=Issac|year= 1793|chapter=[[s:Observations upon the Prophecies of Daniel/Part I Chap XI|Of the Times of the Birth and Passion of Christ]]|title=[[s:Observations upon the Prophecies of Daniel|Observations upon the Prophecies of Daniel and the Apocalypse of St. John]]}}</ref> In 1990 astronomer [[Bradley E. Schaefer]] computed the date as Friday, April 3, 33 AD/CE.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Schaefer |first=B. E. |year=1990 |title=Lunar Visibility and the Crucifixion |journal=Journal of the Royal Astronomical Society |volume=31 |issue=1 |pages=53<U+2013>67 |bibcode=1990QJRAS..31...53S }}</ref> In 1991, John Pratt stated that Newton's method was sound, but included a minor error at the end. Pratt suggested the year 33 AD/CE as the answer.<ref name=Pratt >{{cite journal |last=Pratt |first=J. P. |year=1991 |title=Newton's Date for the Crucifixion |journal=Journal of the Royal Astronomical Society |volume=32 |issue=3 |pages=301<U+2013>304 |bibcode=1991QJRAS..32..301P }}</ref> Using the different approach of a [[Crucifixion darkness and eclipse|lunar eclipse]] model, [[Colin Humphreys|Humphreys]] and Waddington arrived at the conclusion that Friday, April 3, 33 AD/CE was the date of the crucifixion.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Humphreys|first1=Colin| first2=W. G.|last2= Waddington|title=Dating the Crucifixion |journal=Nature|volume= 306 |year=1983|month=December| pages= 743<U+2013>746|url=http://www.nature.com/nature/journal/v306/n5945/abs/306743a0.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|first1=Colin J.|last1= Humphreys |first2=W. G. |last2=Waddington |title= The Date of the Crucifixion |journal= Journal of the American Scientific Affiliation|volume= 37 |month=March |year=1985|url=http://www.asa3.org/ASA/PSCF/1985/JASA3-85Humphreys.html.| archivedate= 2013-02-18|archiveurl= http://www.webcitation.org/6EWXaQaf2|deadurl=yes}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|first=Colin |last=Humphreys|title= The Mystery of the Last Supper|publisher= Cambridge University Press|year= 2011 |isbn= 978-0-521-73200-0| page= 193 |postscript=. However, note that Humphreys places the Last Supper on a Wednesday.}}</ref>

== Life and teachings in the New Testament ==
{{Main|Life of Jesus in the New Testament}}
{{see also|New Testament places associated with Jesus|Names and titles of Jesus in the New Testament}}

Although the four canonical gospels, [[Gospel of Matthew|Matthew]], [[Gospel of Mark|Mark]], [[Gospel of Luke|Luke]], and [[Gospel of John|John]], are the main sources for the biography of Jesus' life, other parts of the New Testament, such as the [[Pauline epistles]] which were likely written decades before them, also include references to key episodes in his life, such as the [[Last Supper]] in [[s:Bible (American Standard)/1 Corinthians#11:23|1 Corinthians 11:23<U+2013>26]].{{sfn|Blomberg|2009|pp=441<U+2013>442}}<ref name=Fahlbusch52 />{{sfn|Evans|2003|pp=465<U+2013>477}} The [[Acts of the Apostles]] ([[s:Bible (American Standard)/Acts#10:37|10:37<U+2013>38]] and [[s:Bible (American Standard)/Acts#19:4|19:4]]) refers to the early ministry of Jesus and its anticipation by John the Baptist.<ref name="Bruce1988">{{cite book|title=The Book of the Acts|first=Frederick F.|last= Bruce|year= 1988| isbn= 0-8028-2505-2 |page= 362}}</ref>{{sfn|Rausch|2003|p=77}} [[s:Bible (American Standard)/Acts#1:1|Acts 1:1<U+2013>11]] says more about the [[Ascension of Jesus Christ|Ascension episode]] (also mentioned in [[s:Bible (American Standard)/1 Timothy#3:16|1 Timothy 3:16]]) than the canonical gospels.{{sfn|Evans|2003|pp=521<U+2013>530}}

According to the majority viewpoint, the [[Synoptic Gospels]] (Matthew, Mark, and Luke) are the primary sources of historical information about Jesus,{{sfn|Sanders|1993|p=73}}<ref>{{cite encyclopedia | url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/303091/Jesus-Christ |title=Jesus Christ | encyclopedia=Encyclop<U+00E6>dia Britannica | accessdate=2013-04-13|quote=The Synoptic Gospels, then, are the primary sources for knowledge of the historical Jesus.}}</ref> and of the religious movement he founded, but not everything contained in the gospels is considered to be historically reliable.<ref name=HistJesus/> Elements whose historical authenticity are disputed include the two accounts of the [[Nativity of Jesus]], as well as the resurrection and certain details about the crucifixion.{{sfn|Crossan|Watts|1999|p=108}}{{sfn|Dunn|2003|pp=779-781}}<ref name=Funk&Seminar/> Views on the gospels range from the accounts being [[inerrancy|inerrant]] descriptions of the life of Jesus{{sfn|Grudem|1995|pp=90-91}} to the accounts providing no historical information about his life.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Howard M. Teeple |year=1970 |month=March |title=The Oral Tradition That Never Existed |journal=Journal of Biblical Literature |volume=89 |issue=1 |pages=56<U+2013>68 |doi=10.2307/3263638}}</ref>

=== Canonical gospel accounts ===
{{See also|Gospel harmony|Historical reliability of the Gospels|Internal consistency of the New Testament}}
[[File:P. Chester Beatty I, folio 13-14, recto.jpg|thumb|A 3rd-century Greek [[papyrus]] of [[Gospel of Luke|Luke]]]]
Three of the four canonical gospels, namely Matthew, Mark, and Luke, are known as the [[synoptic Gospels]], from the Greek <U+03C3><U+03CD><U+03BD> (syn "together") and <U+1F44><U+03C8><U+03B9><U+03C2> (opsis "view"), given that they display a high degree of similarity in content, narrative arrangement, language and paragraph structure.<ref>{{cite book|title=New Testament Theology|first=Paul |last=Haffner|year=2008 |isbn= 88-902268-0-3 |page= 135}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=A Guide to the Gospels|first=W. Graham|last= Scroggie |year=1995 |isbn= 0-8254-3744-X |page= 128}}</ref><ref name="oed">{{OED|synoptic}}</ref> The presentation in the fourth canonical gospel, John, differs from these three in that it has more of a thematic nature rather than a narrative format.<ref name=Moloney3 /><ref name="CC">{{cite book|first=Will |last=Durant|title= Caesar and Christ|location= New York|publisher= Simon and Schuster|year=1972}}</ref> Scholars generally agree that it is impossible to find any direct literary relationship between the synoptic gospels and the Gospel of John.<ref name=Moloney3 >{{cite book|title=The Gospel of John|first1=Francis J.|last1= Moloney |first2= Daniel J.|last2= Harrington |year=1998| isbn= 0-8146-5806-7 |page= 3}}</ref>

However, in general, the authors of the New Testament showed little interest in an absolute chronology of Jesus or in synchronizing the episodes of his life with the secular history of the age.{{sfn|Rahner|2004|pp=730-731}} The gospels were primarily written as theological documents in the context of [[early Christianity]] with the chronological timelines as a secondary consideration.<ref name=Wiarda75 >{{cite book|title=Interpreting Gospel Narratives: Scenes, People, and Theology|first=Timothy |last=Wiarda |year=2010 |isbn= 0-8054-4843-8 |pages= 75<U+2013>78}}</ref> One manifestation of the gospels being theological documents rather than historical chronicles is that they devote about one third of their text to just seven days, namely the last week of the life of Jesus in Jerusalem, referred to as [[Passion (Christianity)|Passion Week]].<ref name=Turner613 >{{cite book|title=Matthew|first=David L. |last=Turner|year= 2008| isbn= 0-8010-2684-9 |page= 613}}</ref>

Although the gospels do not provide enough details to satisfy the demands of modern historians regarding exact dates, it is possible to draw from them a general picture of the life story of Jesus.{{sfn|Rahner|2004|pp=730-731}}<ref name=Wiarda75 />{{sfn|Sanders|1993|p=3}} However, as stated in [[s:Bible (American Standard)/John#21:25|John 21:25]] the gospels do not claim to provide an exhaustive list of the events in the life of Jesus.<ref>{{cite book|title=Christology: A Biblical, Historical, and Systematic Study of Jesus|authorlink=Gerald O'Collins|last=O'Collins|first=Gerald|year= 2009 |isbn= 0-19-955787-X |pages= 1<U+2013>3}}</ref> Since the 2nd century attempts have been made to ''[[Gospel harmony|harmonize]]'' the gospel accounts into a single narrative; [[Tatian]]'s [[Diatesseron]] perhaps being the first.<ref>{{cite book|title=Augustine through the ages: an encyclopedia|first=John C. |last=Cavadini |year=1999 |isbn= 0-8028-3843-X| page= 132}}
* {{cite book|first=Kurt |last=Aland|year= 1982 |title=Synopsis of the Four Gospels| isbn= 0-8267-0500-6 |pages= 1<U+2013>10}}
* {{cite book|first=John B.|last= Orchard|year= 1983 |title=Synopsis of the Four Gospels |isbn= 0-567-09331-X |pages= 2<U+2013>7}}
* {{harvnb|Cox|2007|p=3}}</ref> There are differences in specific temporal sequences in the gospel accounts, in the parables and miracles listed in each gospel, and while the flow of the some events such as Baptism, Transfiguration and Crucifixion and interactions with people such as the Apostles are shared among the synoptic gospel narratives, events such as the Transfiguration do not appear in John's Gospel which also differs on other issues such as the [[Cleansing of the Temple]].{{sfn|Rahner|2004|pp=730-731}}<ref name=Wiarda75 />{{sfn|Blomberg|2009|pp=224<U+2013>229}}{{sfn|Cox|2007|pp=18<U+2013>20}}

==== Key elements and the five major milestones ====
The five major milestones in the gospel narrative of the life of Jesus are his [[Baptism of Jesus|Baptism]], [[Transfiguration of Jesus|Transfiguration]], [[Crucifixion of Jesus|Crucifixion]], [[Resurrection of Jesus|Resurrection]] and [[Ascension of Jesus|Ascension]].<ref name=digby >{{cite book|title=Essays in New Testament interpretation|authorlink=C. F. D. Moule|first=Charles F. D. |last=Moule |year=1982 |isbn= 0-521-23783-1 |page= 63}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=The Melody of Faith: Theology in an Orthodox Key |first= Vigen |last=Guroian|year= 2010 |isbn= 0-8028-6496-1 |page= 28}}</ref><ref name=JBreck12 /> These are usually bracketed by two other episodes: his Nativity at the beginning and the [[Pentecost|sending]] of the [[Holy Spirit (Christianity)|Holy Spirit]] at the end.<ref name=digby /><ref name=JBreck12 >{{cite book|title=Scripture in tradition|first=John |last=Breck|year=2001| isbn= 0-88141-226-0 |page= 12}}</ref> The gospel accounts of the teachings of Jesus are often presented in terms of specific categories involving his "works and words", e.g. his [[Ministry of Jesus|ministry]], [[Parables of Jesus|parables]] and [[Miracles of Jesus|miracles]].{{sfn|Walvoord|Zuck|1983|p=100}}<ref name=WPent212 >{{cite book|title=The words and works of Jesus Christ|first=J. Dwight |last=Pentecost |year=2000 |isbn= 978-0-310-30940-6 |page= 212}}</ref>

The gospels include a number of discourses by Jesus on specific occasions, such as the [[Sermon on the Mount]] or the [[Farewell Discourse]]. They also include over 30 parables, spread throughout the narrative, often with themes that relate to the sermons.<ref name="autogenerated174">{{cite book|title=All the Parables of the Bible|first=Herbert |last=Lockyer|year= 1988 |isbn= 978-0-310-28111-5 |page= 174}}</ref> [[s:Bible (American Standard)/John#14:10|John 14:10]] stresses the importance of the words of Jesus, and attributes them to the authority of God the Father.<ref name="JDPentecost10">{{cite book|first=J. Dwight|last= Pentecost|year= 1998 |title=The parables of Jesus: lessons in life from the Master Teacher| isbn= 0-8254-3458-0 |page= 10}}</ref><ref name="autogenerated98">{{cite book|first=Eric F.|last= Osborn|year= 1993 |title=The emergence of Christian theology| isbn= 0-521-43078-X |page= 98}}</ref> The gospel episodes that include descriptions of the miracle of Jesus also often include teachings, providing an intertwining of his "words and works" in the gospels.<ref name=WPent212 /><ref name="autogenerated95">{{cite book|first=Graham H. |last=Twelftree|title= Jesus the miracle worker: a historical & theological study| isbn= 0-8308-1596-1 |page =95}}</ref>

=== Genealogy and Nativity ===
{{Gospel Jesus}}
{{Main|Genealogy of Jesus|Nativity of Jesus}}
The accounts of the [[Genealogy of Jesus|genealogy]] and Nativity of Jesus in the New Testament appear only in the Gospel of Luke and the Gospel of Matthew. While there are documents outside of the New Testament which are more or less contemporary with Jesus and the gospels, many shed no light on the more biographical aspects of his life and these two gospel accounts remain the main sources of information on the genealogy and Nativity.{{sfn|Sanders|1993|p=3}}

Matthew begins his gospel in [[s:Bible (American Standard)/Matthew#1:1|1:1]] with the genealogy of Jesus, and presents it before the account of the birth of Jesus, while Luke discusses the genealogy in chapter 3, after the Baptism of Jesus in [[s:Bible (American Standard)/Luke#3:23|Luke 3:22]] when the voice from Heaven addresses Jesus and identifies him as the [[Son of God]].<ref name=MaryBrown /> At that point Luke traces Jesus' ancestry through [[Adam]] to God.<ref name=MaryBrown >{{cite book|title=Mary in the New Testament|first= Raymond E.|last= Brown|year= 1978 |isbn= 0-8091-2168-9 |page= 163}}</ref>

The Nativity is a prominent element in the Gospel of Luke. It comprises over 10 percent of the text, and is three times the length of the nativity text in Matthew.{{sfn|Boring|Craddock|2004|page=177}} Luke's account takes place mostly before the birth of Jesus and centers on Mary, while Matthew's takes place mostly after the birth of Jesus and centers on Joseph.{{sfn|Mills|Bullard|1998|p=556}}<ref name="marsh37">{{cite book |title=Jesus and the Gospels |author=Marsh, Clive |author2=Moyise, Steve |year=2006 |isbn=978-0-567-04073-2 |page=37 |location =New York |publisher=Clark International}}</ref>{{sfn|Morris|1992|page=26}} According to Luke and Matthew, Jesus was born to [[Saint Joseph|Joseph]] and [[Mary (mother of Jesus)|Mary]], his [[betrothed]], in [[Bethlehem]]. Both support the doctrine of the [[Virgin birth of Jesus|Virgin Birth]] in which Jesus was miraculously conceived in his mother's womb by the Holy Spirit, when his mother was still a virgin.<ref name=Jeffrey>{{cite book |title=A Dictionary of biblical tradition in English literature |last=Jeffrey|first= David L. |year=1992 |isbn=978-0-85244-224-1 |pages=538<U+2013>540 |location=Grand Rapids, MI |publisher= Wm. B. Eerdmans Publishing |url=http://books.google.com/books?id=7R0IGTSvIVIC&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Cox|2007|pp=30<U+2013>37}}
* {{cite book |title=Who's Who in the New Testament |author=Brownrigg, Ronald |year=2002 |isbn=978-0-415-26036-7 |pages=96<U+2013>100 |location=London |publisher=Taylor & Francis}}
* {{cite book |title=The Birth of Jesus According to the Gospels |author=Kelly, Joseph F. |year=2008 |isbn=978-0-8146-2948-2 |pages=41<U+2013>49 |location=Collegeville, MN |publisher=Liturgical Press}}</ref>

In [[s:Bible (American Standard)/Luke#1:31|Luke 1:31<U+2013>38]] Mary learns from the angel [[Gabriel]] that she will conceive and bear a child called Jesus through the action of the Holy Spirit.<ref name="marsh37"/><ref name=Jeffrey/> Following his betrothal to Mary, Joseph is troubled in [[s:Bible (American Standard)/Matthew#1:19|Matthew 1:19<U+2013>20]] because Mary is pregnant, but in the first of [[St. Joseph's dream|Joseph's three dreams]] an angel assures him not be afraid to take Mary as his wife, because her child was conceived by the Holy Spirit.{{sfn|Talbert|2010|pp=29<U+2013>30}} When Mary is due to give [[Virgin birth of Jesus|birth]], she and Joseph travel from [[Nazareth]] to Joseph's ancestral home in Bethlehem to register in the [[census of Quirinius]]. In [[s:Bible (American Standard)/Luke#2:1|Luke 2:1<U+2013>7]]. Mary gives birth to Jesus and, having found no room for themselves in the inn, places the newborn in a [[manger]]. An [[Annunciation to the shepherds|angel visits the shepherds]] and sends them to [[Adoration of the shepherds|adore the child]] in [[s:Bible (American Standard)/Luke#2:22|Luke 2:22]]. After presenting Jesus at the Temple, Joseph and Mary return home to Nazareth.<ref name="marsh37"/><ref name=Jeffrey/> In [[s:Bible (American Standard)/Matthew#2:1|Matthew 1:1<U+2013>12]], the [[Biblical Magi|Wise Men]] or [[Magi]] bring gifts to the young Jesus as the [[Jesus, King of the Jews|King of the Jews]]. King Herod hears of Jesus' birth, but before the [[Massacre of the Innocents]] Joseph is [[St. Joseph's dream|warned by an angel in his dream]] and the family [[Flight to Egypt|flees to Egypt]], after which they return and settle in Nazareth.{{sfn|Talbert|2010|pp=29<U+2013>30}}<ref name="Harris Matthew">{{cite book|authorlink=Stephen L. Harris|last=Harris|first= Stephen L.|title= Understanding the Bible|location= Palo Alto|publisher= Mayfield|year= 1985|pages= 272<U+2013>85.}}</ref>{{sfn|Schnackenburg|2002|pp=9<U+2013>11}}

=== Early life and profession ===
{{Main|Child Jesus}}
{{See also|Return of young Jesus to Nazareth}}
In the Gospels of Luke and Matthew, Jesus' childhood home is identified as the town of Nazareth in [[Galilee]]. Joseph, husband of Mary, appears in descriptions of Jesus' childhood and no mention is made of him thereafter.<ref>{{cite book|title=Saint Joseph: His Life and His Role in the Church Today|first=Louise B.|last= Perrotta|year= 2000 |isbn= 0-87973-573-2 |pages= 21, 110<U+2013>112}}</ref> The New Testament books of Matthew, Mark, and [[Epistle to the Galatians|Galatians]] mention Jesus' brothers and sisters, but the Greek word ''adelphos'' in these verses, has also been translated as brother or kinsman.{{sfn|Bromiley|1988|p=551}}

In [[s:Bible (American Standard)/Mark#6:3|Mark 6:3]] Jesus is called a ''tekton'' (<U+03C4><U+03AD><U+03BA><U+03C4><U+03C9><U+03BD> in Greek), usually understood to mean [[carpenter]]. [[s:Bible (American Standard)/Matthew#13:55|Matthew 13:55]] says he was the son of a ''tekton''.<ref name="Vine1940" />{{rp|170}} ''Tekton'' has been traditionally translated into English as "carpenter", but it is a rather general word (from the same root that leads to "technical" and "technology") that could cover makers of objects in various materials, even builders.{{sfn|Liddell|Scott|1889|p=797}}<ref>{{cite book|last=Dickson|first= John |title=Jesus: A Short Life|publisher= Kregel Publications|year= 2008| isbn= 978-0-8254-7802-4|pages= 68<U+2013>69}}</ref> Beyond the New Testament accounts, the specific association of the profession of Jesus with woodworking is a constant in the traditions of the 1st and 2nd centuries and [[Justin Martyr]] (d. ca. 165) wrote that Jesus made [[yoke]]s and [[plough]]s.<ref>{{cite book|last=Fiensy |first= David |title=Jesus the Galilean| publisher=Gorgias Press|year= 2007|isbn= 1-59333-313-7 |page= 74}}</ref>

=== Baptism and temptation ===
{{Main|Temptation of Christ|Baptism of Jesus}}
[[File:Trevisani baptism christ.JPG|thumb|left|upright|[[Francesco Trevisani|Trevisani]]'s depiction of the typical baptismal scene with the sky opening and the Holy Spirit descending as a dove, 1723<ref>{{cite book|title=Medieval art: a topical dictionary|first= Leslie|last= Ross |year=1996 |isbn= 978-0-313-29329-0 |page= 30}}</ref>]]
In the gospels, the accounts of the Baptism of Jesus are always preceded by information about John the Baptist and his ministry.{{sfn|Blomberg|2009|pp=224<U+2013>229}}{{sfn|K<U+00F6>stenberger|Kellum|Quarles|2009|pp=141<U+2013>143}}<ref name=Alister16 /> In these accounts, John was preaching for penance and repentance for the remission of sins and encouraged the giving of [[alms]] to the poor ([[s:Bible (American Standard)/Luke#3:11|Luke 3:11]]) as he baptized people in the area of the River Jordan around [[Perea (Holy Land)|Perea]] about the time of the commencement of the ministry of Jesus. The Gospel of John ([[s:Bible (American Standard)/John#1:28|1:28]]) specifies "Bethany beyond the Jordan", that is [[Bethabara]] in Perea, when it initially refers to it and later
[[s:Bible (American Standard)/John#3:23|John 3:23]] refers to further baptisms in [[<U+00C6>non]] "because there was much water there".<ref>{{cite book|title=Big Picture of the Bible <U+2013> New Testament|first=Lorna D. |last=Nichols |year=2009 |isbn= 1-57921-928-4 |page= 12}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=John|first=Gerard S.|last= Sloyan|year= 1987| isbn= 0-8042-3125-7 |page= 11}}</ref>

The four gospels are not the only references to John's ministry around the River Jordan. In [[s:Bible (American Standard)/Acts#10:37|Acts 10:37<U+2013>38]], Peter refers to how the ministry of Jesus followed "the baptism which John preached".{{sfn|Rausch|2003|p=77}} In the [[Antiquities of the Jews]] (18.5.2) 1st century historian Josephus also wrote about John the Baptist and his eventual death in Perea.{{sfn|Freedman|2000|p=583}}<ref>{{cite book|title=Behold the Man: The Real Life of the Historical Jesus|first=Kirk |last=Kimball |year= 2002 |isbn= 978-1-58112-633-4| page= 654}}</ref>

In the gospels, John had been foretelling ([[s:Bible (American Standard)/Luke#3:16|Luke 3:16]]) of the arrival of a someone "mightier than I".<ref name=EerRoger >{{cite book|title=Eerdmans commentary on the Bible|first1=James D. G.|last1= Dunn|first2= John W. |last2=Rogerson|year= 2003 |isbn= 0-8028-3711-5 |page= 1010}}</ref>{{sfn|Zanzig|2000|p=118}} [[Apostle Paul]] also refers to this anticipation by John in [[s:Bible (American Standard)/Acts#19:4|Acts 19:4]].<ref name="Bruce1988"/> In [[s:Bible (American Standard)/Matthew#3:14|Matthew 3:14]], upon meeting Jesus, the Baptist states: "I need to be baptized by you." However, Jesus persuades John to baptize him nonetheless.{{sfn|Majern<U+00ED>k|Ponessa|Manhardt|2005|pp= 27<U+2013>31}} In the baptismal scene, after Jesus emerges from the water, the sky opens and a voice from Heaven states: "This is my beloved Son with whom I am well pleased". The Holy Spirit then descends upon Jesus as a dove in [[s:Bible (American Standard)/Matthew#3:13|Matthew 3:13<U+2013>17]], [[s:Bible (American Standard)/Mark#1:9|Mark 1:9<U+2013>11]], [[s:Bible (American Standard)/Luke#3:21|Luke 3:21<U+2013>23]].<ref name=EerRoger />{{sfn|Zanzig|2000|p=118}}{{sfn|Majern<U+00ED>k|Ponessa|Manhardt|2005|pp= 27<U+2013>31}} In [[s:Bible (American Standard)/John#1:29|John 1:29<U+2013>33]] rather than a direct narrative, the Baptist bears witness to the episode.{{sfn|Zanzig|2000|p=118}}{{sfn|Brown|1988|pp= 25<U+2013>27}} This is one of two cases in the gospels where a voice from Heaven calls Jesus "[[Son of God|Son]]", the other being in the [[Transfiguration of Jesus]] episode.{{sfn|Lee|2005|pp=21<U+2013>30}}<ref name="Nobbs"/>

After the baptism, the synoptic gospels proceed to describe the [[Temptation of Jesus]], but [[s:Bible (American Standard)/John#1:35|John 1:35<U+2013>37]] narrates the first encounter between Jesus and two of his future disciples, who were then disciples of John the Baptist.{{sfn|Boring|Craddock|2004|pages= 292<U+2013>293}}{{sfn|Niswonger|1992|pp=143<U+2013>146}} In this narrative, the next day the Baptist sees Jesus again and calls him the [[Lamb of God]] and the "two disciples heard him speak, and they followed Jesus".{{sfn|Brown|1988|pp= 25<U+2013>27}}{{sfn|Boring|Craddock|2004|pages= 292<U+2013>293}}<ref>{{cite book|title=Jesus of Nazareth|first=Duane S.|last= Crowther|year= 1999 |isbn= 0-88290-656-9 |page= 77}}
* {{harvnb|Redford|2007|p=92}}
* {{cite book|title=A Summary of Christian History|first1=Robert A.|last1= Baker|first2= John M.|last2= Landers|year= 2005 |isbn= 0-8054-3288-4| pages= 6<U+2013>7}}
* {{cite book|title=The Disciple Whom Jesus Loved| first= J.|last= Phillips |year=2004 |isbn= 0-9702687-1-8 |pages= 121<U+2013>123}}</ref>

=== Ministry ===
{{Main|Ministry of Jesus}}
[[File:Ancient Galilee.jpg|thumb|upright|A 1923 map of [[Galilee]] around 50 AD/CE. Nazareth is towards the center.]]
[[s:Bible (American Standard)/Luke#3:23|Luke 3:23]] states that Jesus was "about 30 years of age" at the start of his ministry.{{sfn|K<U+00F6>stenberger|Kellum|Quarles|2009|p=140}}{{sfn|Maier|1989|pp=113-129}} The date of the start of his ministry has been estimated at around 27<U+2013>29 AD/CE, based on independent approaches which combine separate gospel accounts with other historical data.{{sfn|K<U+00F6>stenberger|Kellum|Quarles|2009|p=140}}{{sfn|Maier|1989|pp=113-129}}<ref name=Scarola /><ref name=Tempvisit /> The end of his ministry is estimated to be in the range 30<U+2013>36 AD/CE.{{sfn|K<U+00F6>stenberger|Kellum|Quarles|2009|p=140}}{{sfn|Barnett|2002|p=19-21}}{{sfn|Maier|1989|pp=113-129}}{{sfn|Sanders|1993|pp=11, 249}}

The gospel accounts place the beginning of Jesus' ministry in the countryside of Judea, near the [[River Jordan]].<ref name=Alister16 >{{cite book|title=Christianity: an introduction|first= Alister E.|last= McGrath|year= 2006 |isbn= 978-1-4051-0901-7| pages= 16<U+2013>22}}</ref> Jesus' ministry begins with his Baptism by John the Baptist ([[s:Bible (American Standard)/Matthew#3:13|Matthew 3]], [[s:Bible (American Standard)/Luke#3:21|Luke 3]]), and ends with the [[Last Supper]] with his disciples ([[s:Bible (American Standard)/Matthew#26:26|Matthew 26]], [[s:Bible (American Standard)/Luke#22:17|Luke 22]]) in Jerusalem.{{sfn|K<U+00F6>stenberger|Kellum|Quarles|2009|pp=141<U+2013>143}}<ref name=Alister16 /> The gospels present John the Baptist's ministry as the precursor to that of Jesus and the Baptism as marking the beginning of Jesus' ministry, after which Jesus travels, preaches and performs miracles.{{sfn|Blomberg|2009|pp=224<U+2013>229}}{{sfn|K<U+00F6>stenberger|Kellum|Quarles|2009|pp=141<U+2013>143}}<ref name=Alister16 />

The ''Early Galilean ministry'' begins when Jesus goes back to Galilee from the [[Judaean Desert]] after rebuffing the [[Temptation of Christ|temptation of Satan]].{{sfn|Morris|1992|page=71}} In this early period Jesus preaches around Galilee and in [[s:Bible (American Standard)/Matthew#4:18|Matthew 4:18<U+2013>20]] [[first disciples of Jesus|his first disciples]] encounter him, begin to travel with him and eventually form the core of the early Church.<ref name=Alister16 />{{sfn|Redford|2007|pp=117<U+2013>130}} This period includes the [[Sermon on the Mount]], one of the major discourses of Jesus.{{sfn|Redford|2007|pp=117<U+2013>130}}<ref>{{cite book|title=The Sermon on the mount: a theological investigation|first=Carl G.|last= Vaught|year=2001 |isbn =978-0-918954-76-3 |pages= xi<U+2013>xiv}}</ref>

The ''Major Galilean ministry'' which begins in [[Matthew 8]] refers to activities up to the [[death of John the Baptist]]. It includes the [[Calming the storm]] and a number of other [[Miracles of Jesus|miracles]] and [[parables of Jesus|parables]].<ref>{{cite book |title=A theology of the New Testament|first=George E.|last= Ladd |year=1993| page= 324}}</ref>{{sfn|Redford|2007|pp=143<U+2013>160}} The ''Final Galilean ministry'' includes the [[Feeding the 5000]] and [[Jesus' walk on water|Walking on water]] episodes, both in [[s:Bible (American Standard)/Matthew#14:13|Matthew 14]].{{sfn|Cox|2007|p=97<U+2013>110}}{{sfn|Redford|2007|pp=165<U+2013>180}} The end of this period (as Matthew 16 and Mark 8 end) establishes a turning point in the ministry of Jesus with the dual episodes of [[Confession of Peter]] and the [[Transfiguration of Jesus|Transfiguration]].<ref name= "Barton132">{{cite book|title=The Cambridge companion to the Gospels|first=Stephen C.|last= Barton |isbn= 0-521-00261-3 |pages= 132<U+2013>133}}</ref><ref name=KingsburyMark />{{sfn|Cox|2007|p=121<U+2013>135}}{{sfn|Redford|2007|pp=189<U+2013>207}}

As Jesus travels towards Jerusalem, in the ''Later [[Perea (Bible)|Perean]] ministry'', about one-third the way down from the Sea of Galilee along the Jordan, he returns to the area where he was baptized, and in [[s:Bible (American Standard)/John#10:40|John 10:40<U+2013>42]].{{sfn|Mills|Bullard|1998|p=929}}<ref>{{harvnb|Cox|2007|p=137}}
* {{harvnb|Redford|2007| pp= 211<U+2013>229}}
* {{cite book|title=Preaching Matthew's Gospel|first=Richard A.|last= Jensen |year=1998 |isbn =978-0-7880-1221-1 |pages= 25, 158}}
* {{cite book|title=Behold the King: A Study of Matthew|first= Stanley D.|last= Toussaint |year=2005 |isbn= 0-8254-3845-4 |pages= 215<U+2013>216}}</ref> The ''Final ministry in Jerusalem'' is sometimes called the ''Passion Week'' and begins with the Jesus' triumphal entry into Jerusalem on [[Palm Sunday]].{{sfn|Cox|2007|pp=155<U+2013>170}} In that week in the synoptic gospels Jesus [[Cleansing of the Temple|drives the money changers]] from the Temple, and [[Bargain of Judas|Judas bargains to betray]] him. John's Gospel places the Temple incident during the early part of Jesus' ministry, and scholars differ on whether these are one or two separate incidents.{{sfn|Evans|2005|p=49}} This period culminates in the [[Last Supper]], and the [[Farewell discourse]]. The accounts of the ministry of Jesus generally end with the Last Supper.{{sfn|Blomberg|2009|pp=224<U+2013>229}}{{sfn|Cox|2007|pp=155<U+2013>170}}{{sfn|Redford|2007|pp=257<U+2013>274}}

=== Teachings and preachings ===
{{Main|Sermon on the Mount|Parables of Jesus}}
{{See also|Sermon on the Plain|Five Discourses of Matthew|Farewell Discourse|Olivet Discourse}}
[[File:Jesus-Christ-from-Hagia-Sophia.jpg|thumb|upright|Jesus Christ [[Pantocrator]] <U+2013> ancient [[mosaic]] from [[Hagia Sophia]]]]

In the New Testament the teachings of Jesus are presented in terms of his "words and works".{{sfn|Walvoord|Zuck|1983|p=100}}<ref name=WPent212 /> The words of Jesus include a number of sermons, as well as [[Parables of Jesus|parables]] that appear throughout the narrative of the synoptic gospels (the Gospel of John includes no parables). The works include the [[Miracles of Jesus|miracles]] and other acts performed during his ministry.<ref name=WPent212 /> Although the canonical gospels are the major source of the teachings of Jesus, the [[Pauline epistles]], which were likely written decades before the gospels, provide some of the earliest written accounts of the teachings of Jesus.{{sfn|Blomberg|2009|pp=441<U+2013>442}}

The New Testament does not present the teachings of Jesus as merely his own preachings, but equates the words of Jesus with divine revelation, with John the Baptist stating in [[s:Bible (NIV)/John#3:34|John 3:34]]: "For the one whom God has sent speaks the words of God, for God gives the Spirit without limit"; and in [[s:Bible (NIV)/John#7:16|John 7:16]]: "Jesus answered, 'My teaching is not my own. It comes from the one who sent me.{{'"}} Again he re-asserted that in [[s:Bible (NIV)/John#14:10|John 14:10]]: "Don't you believe that I am in the Father, and that the Father is in me? The words I say to you I do not speak on my own authority. Rather, it is the Father, living in me, who is doing his work."<ref name="autogenerated98"/><ref>{{cite book|title=The missions of Jesus and the disciples according to the Fourth Gospel| first=Andreas J.|last= K<U+00F6>stenberger|year= 1998| isbn= 0-8028-4255-0 |pages= 108<U+2013>109}}</ref> In [[s:Bible (NIV)/Matthew#11:27|Matthew 11:27]] Jesus claims divine knowledge, stating: "No one knows the Son except the Father and no one knows the Father except the Son", asserting the mutual knowledge he has with the Father.{{sfn|Bromiley|1988|pp=571<U+2013>572}}{{sfn|Talbert|2010|p=149}}

Parables represent a major component of the teachings of Jesus in the gospels, the approximately thirty parables forming about one third of his recorded teachings.<ref name="autogenerated174"/><ref name="JDPentecost10" /> The parables may appear within longer sermons, as well as other places within the narrative.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Sermons of Jesus the Messiah|first= E. Keith|last= Howick|year= 2003 |isbn= 978-1-886249-02-8| pages= 7<U+2013>9}}</ref> Jesus' parables are seemingly simple and memorable stories, often with imagery, and each conveys a teaching which usually relates the physical world to the [[Spirituality|spiritual]] world.<ref>{{cite book|first=Friedrich G. |last= Lisco |year=1850 |title=The Parables of Jesus|publisher= Daniels and Smith Publishers|location= Philadelphia| pages= 9<U+2013>11}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|first=Ashton |last=Oxenden|year= 1864 |title=The parables of our Lord? |publisher=William Macintosh Publishers|location= London| page= 6}}</ref>

The gospel episodes that include descriptions of the miracle of Jesus also often include teachings, providing an intertwining of his "words and works" in the gospels.<ref name=WPent212 /><ref name="autogenerated95"/> Many of the miracles in the gospels teach the importance of faith, for instance in [[Cleansing ten lepers]] and [[Daughter of Jairus]] the beneficiaries are told that they were healed due to their faith.{{sfn|Donahue|Harrington|2002|p= 182}}<ref>{{cite book|last=Lockyer|first= Herbert|year= 1988 |title=All the Miracles of the Bible| isbn= 0-310-28101-6 |page= 235}}</ref>

=== Proclamation as Christ and Transfiguration ===
{{Main|Confession of Peter|Transfiguration of Jesus}}

[[File:Transfiguration by Lodovico Carracci.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Transfiguration of Jesus]] depicting him with [[Elijah]], [[Moses]] and 3 apostles by [[Lodovico Carracci|Carracci]], 1594]]

At about the middle of each of the three synoptic gospels, two related episodes mark a turning point in the narrative: the Confession of Peter and the [[Transfiguration of Jesus]].<ref name="Barton132"/><ref name="KingsburyMark">{{cite book|title=The Christology of Mark's Gospel|first= Jack D. |last= Kingsbury |year=1983 |isbn= 0-8006-2337-1 |pages= 91<U+2013>95}}</ref> These episodes begin in [[Caesarea Philippi]] just north of the [[Sea of Galilee]] at the beginning of the final journey to [[Jerusalem]] which ends in the [[Passion (Christianity)|Passion]] and [[Resurrection of Jesus]].<ref name="Karris">{{cite book|title=The Collegeville Bible Commentary: New Testament |first=Robert J.|last= Karris|year= 1992 |isbn= 0-8146-2211-9 |pages= 885<U+2013>886}}</ref> These episodes mark the beginnings of the gradual disclosure of the identity of Jesus to his disciples; and his prediction of his own suffering and death.{{sfn|Lee|2005|pp=21<U+2013>30}}<ref name="Nobbs" /><ref name="Barton132" /><ref name="KingsburyMark" /><ref name="Karris" />

Peter's Confession begins as a dialogue between Jesus and his disciples in [[s:Bible (American Standard)/Matthew#16:13|Matthew 16:13]], [[s:Bible (American Standard)/Mark#8:27|Mark 8:27]] and [[s:Bible (American Standard)/Luke#9:18|Luke 9:18]]. Jesus asks his disciples: "But who do you say that I am?" Simon Peter answers him: "You are the Christ, the Son of the living God."<ref name="Karris" /><ref>{{cite book|title=Who do you say that I am? Essays on Christology|first1=Jack D.|last1= Kingsbury| first2=Mark A.|last2= Powell|first3= David R. |last3=Bauer |year=1999 |isbn= 0-664-25752-6 |page= xvi}}</ref>{{sfn|Donahue|Harrington|2002|p= 336}} In [[s:Bible (NIV)/Matthew#16:17|Matthew 16:17]] Jesus replied, "Blessed are you, Simon son of Jonah, for this was not revealed to you by flesh and blood, but by my Father in heaven". In blessing Peter, Jesus not only accepts the titles "[[Christ]]" and "[[Son of God]]" which Peter attributes to him, but declares the proclamation a divine revelation by stating that his [[God the Father|Father in Heaven]] had revealed it to Peter.<ref name="OneTeacher">{{cite book|title=One teacher: Jesus' teaching role in Matthew's gospel|first= John Y. H.|last= Yieh |year=2004|isbn =978-3-11-018151-7| pages= 240<U+2013>241|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=g0-NaraCrAoC&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref> In this assertion, by endorsing both titles as divine revelation, Jesus unequivocally declares himself to be both Christ and the Son of God.<ref name="OneTeacher" />{{sfn|Pannenberg|1968|pp=53-54}}

The account of the [[Transfiguration of Jesus]] appears in [[s:Bible (American Standard)/Matthew#17:1|Matthew 17:1<U+2013>9]], [[s:Bible (American Standard)/Mark#9:2|Mark 9:2<U+2013>8]], and [[s:Bible (American Standard)/Luke#9:28|Luke 9:28<U+2013>36]].{{sfn|Lee|2005|pp=21<U+2013>30}}<ref name="Nobbs">{{cite book|title=The Content and the Setting of the Gospel Tradition|first1=Mark |last1=Harding|first2= Alanna |last2=Nobbs |year=2010 |isbn= 978-0-8028-3318-1 |pages= 281<U+2013>282}}</ref><ref name="Barton132"/> Jesus takes Peter and two other apostles with him and goes up to a mountain, which is not named. Once on the mountain, Matthew (17:2) states that Jesus "was transfigured before them; his face shining as the sun, and his garments became white as the light".{{sfn|Lee|2005|pp=72<U+2013>76}} A bright cloud appears around them, and a voice from the cloud states: "This is my beloved Son, with whom I am well pleased; listen to him".{{sfn|Lee|2005|pp=21<U+2013>30}} The Transfiguration not only supports the identity of Jesus as the [[Son of God]] (as in his Baptism), but the statement "listen to him" identifies him as the messenger and mouth-piece of God.<ref name="Meta47">{{cite book|title=Metamorphosis: the Transfiguration in Byzantine theology and iconography|first=Andreas |last=Andreopoulos |year=2005 |isbn= 0-88141-295-3 |pages= 47<U+2013>49}}</ref>

=== Final week: betrayal, arrest, trial, and death ===
[[File:<U+00DA>ltima Cena - Juan de Juanes.jpg|thumb|left|The [[Last Supper]] has been depicted by many artistic masters,<ref>{{cite book|title=Gospel figures in art|first=Stefano |last=Zuffi |year=2003 |isbn= 978-0-89236-727-6 |pages= 254<U+2013>259}}</ref> including this 16th century painting by Joan de Joanes.]]
The description of the last week of the life of Jesus (often called the [[Passion week]]) occupies about one third of the narrative in the canonical gospels.<ref name=Turner613 /> The narrative for that week starts by a description of the [[Triumphal entry into Jerusalem|final entry]] into Jerusalem, and ends with his crucifixion.{{sfn|Blomberg|2009|pp=224<U+2013>229}}{{sfn|Cox|2007|pp=155<U+2013>170}}

The last week in Jerusalem is the conclusion of the journey which Jesus had started in Galilee through [[Perea (Bible)|Perea]] and Judea.{{sfn|Cox|2007|pp=155<U+2013>170}} Just before the account of the final entry of Jesus into Jerusalem, the Gospel of John includes the [[Raising of Lazarus]] episode, which builds the tension between Jesus and the authorities.{{sfn|Cox|2007|pp=155<U+2013>170}}

==== Final entry into Jerusalem ====
{{Main|Triumphal entry into Jerusalem|Cleansing of the Temple|Bargain of Judas}}
[[File:G<U+00E9>r<U+00F4>me - L'entr<U+00E9>e du Christ <U+00E0> J<U+00E9>rusalem - cadre.jpg|thumb|A painting of Jesus' final entry into Jerusalem, by [[Jean-L<U+00E9>on G<U+00E9>r<U+00F4>me]] in 1897]]

In the four canonical gospels, Jesus' [[Triumphal entry into Jerusalem]] takes place at the beginning of the last week of his life, a few days before the [[Last Supper]], marking the beginning of the [[Passion (Christianity)|Passion narrative]].{{sfn|Majern<U+00ED>k|Ponessa|Manhardt|2005|pp=133<U+2013>134}}{{sfn|Boring|Craddock|2004|pages=256<U+2013>258}}{{sfn|Evans|2003|pp=381<U+2013>395}}{{sfn|Evans|2005|pp=114<U+2013>118}}<ref>[[s:Bible (American Standard)/Matthew#21:1|Matthew 21:1<U+2013>11]], [[s:Bible (American Standard)/Mark#11:1|Mark 11:1<U+2013>11]], [[s:Bible (American Standard)/Luke#19:28|Luke 19:28<U+2013>44]] [[s:Bible (American Standard)/John#12:12|John 12:12<U+2013>19]]</ref> After leaving [[Bethany (Biblical village)|Bethany]] Jesus rides a donkey into Jerusalem, with Mark and John specifying Sunday, Matthew Monday, and Luke not mentioning the day.{{sfn|Majern<U+00ED>k|Ponessa|Manhardt|2005|pp=133<U+2013>134}}{{sfn|Boring|Craddock|2004|pages=256<U+2013>258}}{{sfn|Evans|2003|pp=381<U+2013>395}} As Jesus rode into Jerusalem the people there laid down their cloaks in front of him, and also lay down small branches of trees and sang part of [[s:Bible (American Standard)/Psalms#118:25|Psalm 118: 25<U+2013>26]].{{sfn|Majern<U+00ED>k|Ponessa|Manhardt|2005|pp=133<U+2013>134}}<ref name=MacArthur17 >{{cite book|title=John 12<U+2013>21|first= John |last=MacArthur |year=2008 |isbn= 978-0-8024-0824-2 |pages= 17<U+2013>18}}</ref>{{sfn|Boring|Craddock|2004|pages=256<U+2013>258}}{{sfn|Evans|2003|pp=381<U+2013>395}} The cheering crowds who greeted Jesus he entered Jerusalem added to the tension between him and the authorities.{{sfn|Cox|2007|pp=155<U+2013>170}}

In the three synoptic gospels, entry into Jerusalem is followed by the [[Cleansing of the Temple]] episode, in which Jesus expels the money changers from the Temple, accusing them of turning the Temple to a den of thieves through their commercial activities. This is the only account of Jesus using physical force in any of the gospels.{{sfn|Bromiley|1988|pp=571<U+2013>572}}{{sfn|Evans|2005|p=49}}<ref name=Anderson158 >{{cite book|title=The Fourth Gospel And the Quest for Jesus|first= Paul N.|last= Anderson |year=2006 |isbn= 0-567-04394-0 |page= 158}}</ref> [[s:Bible (American Standard)/John#2:13|John 2:13<U+2013>16]] includes a similar narrative much earlier, and scholars debate if these refer to the same episode.{{sfn|Bromiley|1988|pp=571<U+2013>572}}{{sfn|Evans|2005|p=49}}<ref name=Anderson158 /> The synoptics include a number of well known [[parables of Jesus|parables]] and sermons such as the [[Widow's mite]] and the [[Second Coming Prophecy]] during the week that follows.{{sfn|Boring|Craddock|2004|pages=256<U+2013>258}}{{sfn|Evans|2003|pp=381<U+2013>395}}

In that week, the synoptics also narrate conflicts between Jesus and the elders of the Jews, in episodes such as the [[Authority of Jesus Questioned]] and the [[Woes of the Pharisees]] in which Jesus criticizes their hypocrisy.{{sfn|Boring|Craddock|2004|pages=256<U+2013>258}}{{sfn|Evans|2003|pp=381<U+2013>395}} [[Judas Iscariot]], one of the [[twelve apostles]] approaches the Jewish elders and performs the "[[Bargain of Judas]]" in which he accepts to betray Jesus and hand him over to the elders.<ref>[[s:Bible (American Standard)/Matthew#26:14|Matthew 26:14<U+2013>16]], [[s:Bible (American Standard)/Mark#14:10|Mark 14:10<U+2013>11]], [[s:Bible (American Standard)/Luke#22:1|Luke 22:1<U+2013>6]]</ref><ref name=Lockyer106 >{{cite book|title=All the Apostles of the Bible| first=Herbert |last=Lockyer |year=1988 |isbn= 0-310-28011-7 |pages= 106<U+2013>111}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=The Synoptic Gospels and the Book of Acts|first=Doremus A. |last= Hayes |year=2009 |isbn= 1-115-87731-3 |page= 88}}</ref> Matthew specifies the price as [[thirty silver coins]].<ref name="Lockyer106 "/>

==== Last Supper ====
{{Main|Last Supper}}
{{see also|Jesus predicts his betrayal|Denial of Peter|Last Supper in Christian art}}

[[File:Juan de Juanes 002.jpg|thumb|upright|Jesus with the [[Eucharist]] (detail), by [[Juan de Juanes]], mid<U+2013>late 16th century]]
In the New Testament, the Last Supper is the final meal that Jesus shares with his [[Twelve Apostles#The Twelve Apostles|twelve apostles]] in Jerusalem before his crucifixion. The Last Supper is mentioned in all four canonical gospels, and Paul's [[First Epistle to the Corinthians]] ([[s:Bible (American Standard)/1 Corinthians#11:23|11:23<U+2013>26]]), which was likely written before the gospels, also refers to it.<ref name=Fahlbusch52 >{{cite book|title=The encyclopedia of Christianity, Volume 4| first=Erwin |last=Fahlbusch|year= 2005| isbn= 978-0-8028-2416-5 |pages= 52<U+2013>56}}</ref>{{sfn|Evans|2003|pp=465<U+2013>477}}<ref>[[s:Bible (American Standard)/Matthew#26:20|Matthew 26:20]], [[s:Bible (American Standard)/Mark#14:17|Mark 14:17]], [[s:Bible (American Standard)/Luke#22:21<U+2013>23|Luke 22:21<U+2013>23]] [[s:Bible (American Standard)/John#13:1|John 13:1]]</ref>{{sfn|Cox|2007|pp=180<U+2013>191}}

In all four gospels, during the meal, Jesus [[Jesus predicts his betrayal|predicts that]] one of his Apostles will betray him.{{sfn|Cox|2007|p=182}} Jesus is described as reiterating, despite each Apostle's assertion that he would not betray Jesus, that the betrayer would be one of those who were present. In [[s:Bible (American Standard)/Matthew#26:23|Matthew 26:23<U+2013>25]] and [[s:Bible (American Standard)/John#13:26|John 13:26<U+2013>27]] Judas is specifically singled out as the traitor.<ref name=Fahlbusch52 />{{sfn|Evans|2003|pp=465<U+2013>477}}{{sfn|Cox|2007|p=182}}

In [[s:Bible (American Standard)/Matthew#26:26|Matthew 26:26<U+2013>29]], [[s:Bible (American Standard)/Mark#14:22|Mark 14:22<U+2013>25]], [[s:Bible (American Standard)/Luke#22:19|Luke 22:19<U+2013>20]] Jesus takes bread, breaks it and gives it to the disciples, saying: "This is my body which is given for you".<ref name=Fahlbusch52 /><ref>{{cite book|title=Oxford Dictionary of the Christian Church|first1=F. L. |last1=Cross |first2= E. A. |last2=Livingstone|year= 2005| isbn= 978-0-19-280290-3|chapter=Eucharist}}</ref> Although the Gospel of John does not include a description of the bread and wine ritual during the Last Supper, most scholars agree that [[s:Bible (American Standard)/John#6:58|John 6:58<U+2013>59]] (the [[Bread of Life Discourse]]) has a Eucharistic nature and resonates with the "words of institution" used in the synoptic gospels and the Pauline writings on the Last Supper.{{sfn|Freedman|2000|p=792}}

In all four gospels Jesus predicts that Peter will deny knowledge of him, stating that Peter will disown him three times before the [[rooster]] crows the next morning. The synoptics mention that after the [[arrest of Jesus]] Peter denied knowing him three times, but after the third denial, heard the rooster crow and recalled the prediction as Jesus turned to look at him. Peter then began to cry bitterly.<ref>{{cite book|title=Peter: apostle for the whole church|first= Pheme |last=Perkins |year=2000 |isbn= 0-567-08743-3 |page= 85}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=The Gospel according to Matthew, Volume 1|first= Johann P.|last= Lange|year= 1865| publisher= Charles Scribner Co|location= New York| page= 499}}</ref>

The Gospel of John provides the only account of Jesus washing his disciples' feet before the meal.<ref name="Harris Matthew"/> John's Gospel also includes a long sermon by Jesus, preparing his disciples (now without Judas) for his departure. [[s:Bible (American Standard)/John#14:1|Chapters 14<U+2013>17]] of the Gospel of John are known as the ''[[Farewell discourse]]'' given by Jesus, and are a significant source of [[Christology|Christological]] content.<ref name=Gail142 >{{cite book|title=John|first1= Gail R.|last1= O'Day|first2= Susan |last2=Hylen|year=2006 |isbn= 978-0-664-25260-1| pages= 142<U+2013>168}}</ref><ref name=Herman546 >{{cite book|title=The Gospel according to John | authorlink=Herman Nicolaas Ridderbos|first=Herman |last=Ridderbos|year= 1997| isbn= 978-0-8028-0453-2| pages= 546<U+2013>576}}</ref>

==== Agony in the Garden, betrayal and arrest ====
{{Main|Agony in the Garden|Kiss of Judas|Arrest of Jesus}}
{{see also|Holy Hour}}
[[File:Caravaggio - Taking of Christ - Dublin - 2.jpg|thumb|left|A 17th-century depiction of the kiss of Judas and the arrest of Jesus by [[Caravaggio]]]]

In [[s:Bible (American Standard)/Matthew#26:36|Matthew 26:36<U+2013>46]], [[s:Bible (American Standard)/Mark#14:32|Mark 14:32<U+2013>42]], [[s:Bible (American Standard)/Luke#22:39|Luke 22:39<U+2013>46]] and [[s:Bible (American Standard)/John#18:1|John 18:1]], immediately after the Last Supper, Jesus takes a walk to pray, Matthew and Mark identifying this place of prayer as [[Garden of Gethsemane]].{{sfn|Majern<U+00ED>k|Ponessa|Manhardt|2005|p=169}}{{sfn|Walvoord|Zuck|1983|pp=83<U+2013>85}} While in the Garden, [[Judas Iscariot|Judas]] appears, accompanied by a crowd that includes the Jewish priests and elders and people with weapons. Judas [[Kiss of Judas|gives Jesus a kiss]] to identify him to the crowd who then arrests Jesus.{{sfn|Walvoord|Zuck|1983|pp=83<U+2013>85}}{{sfn|Evans|2003|pp=487-500}} One of Jesus' disciples tries to stop them and uses a sword to cut off the ear of one of the men in the crowd.{{sfn|Walvoord|Zuck|1983|pp=83<U+2013>85}}{{sfn|Evans|2003|pp=487-500}} Luke states that Jesus [[miracles of Jesus|miraculously healed]] the wound and John and Matthew state that Jesus criticized the violent act, insisting that his disciples should not resist his arrest. In [[s:Bible (American Standard)/Matthew#26:52|Matthew 26:52]] Jesus makes the well known statement: ''[[Live by the sword, die by the sword|all who live by the sword, shall die by the sword]]''.{{sfn|Walvoord|Zuck|1983|pp=83<U+2013>85}}{{sfn|Evans|2003|pp=487-500}} Prior to the arrest, in [[s:Bible (American Standard)/Matthew#26:31|Matthew 26:31]] Jesus tells the disciples: "All ye shall be offended in me this night" and in [[s:Bible (American Standard)/Matthew#26:32|32]] that: "But after I am raised up, I will go before you into Galilee." After his arrest, Jesus' disciples go into hiding.{{sfn|Walvoord|Zuck|1983|pp=83<U+2013>85}}

==== Trials by the Sanhedrin, Herod and Pilate ====
{{Main|Sanhedrin trial of Jesus|Pilate's Court|Jesus at Herod's Court|Crown of Thorns}}
{{See also|Jesus, King of the Jews|What is truth?}}
In the narrative of the four canonical gospels after the [[arrest of Jesus|betrayal and arrest]] of Jesus, he is taken to the [[Sanhedrin]], a Jewish judicial body.<ref>{{cite book|last=Brown|first= Raymond E|title= An Introduction to the New Testament|publisher= Doubleday |year=1997| isbn= 0-385-24767-2| page= 146}}</ref> Jesus is tried by the Sanhedrin, mocked and beaten and is condemned for making claims of being the [[Son of God]].{{sfn|Evans|2003|pp=487-500}}{{sfn|Blomberg|2009|pp=396<U+2013>400}}<ref name=Holman608 >{{cite book|title=Holman Concise Bible Dictionary|year= 2011 |isbn= 0-8054-9548-7| pages= 608<U+2013>609}}</ref> He is then taken to [[Pontius Pilate]], and the Jewish elders ask Pilate to judge and condemn Jesus<U+2014>accusing him of claiming to be the [[Jesus, King of the Jews|King of the Jews]].<ref name=Holman608 />
After questioning, with few replies provided by Jesus, Pilate publicly declares that he finds Jesus innocent, but the crowd insists on punishment. Pilate then orders Jesus' crucifixion.{{sfn|Evans|2003|pp=487-500}}{{sfn|Blomberg|2009|pp=396<U+2013>400}}<ref name=Holman608 />{{sfn|Bromiley|1988|pp=1050<U+2013>1052}}

[[File:Rembrandt Harmensz. van Rijn 012.jpg|thumb|Jesus in the upper right hand corner, his hands bound behind, is being tried at the high priest's house and turns to look at Peter, in [[Rembrandt]]'s 1660 depiction of [[Denial of Peter|Peter's denial]].<ref>{{cite book|title=The Biblical Rembrandt|first=John I. |last=Durham|year= 2004|publisher=Mercer University Press|isbn=978-0-86554-886-2 |url=http://books.google.com/books?id=o1V_saJPmlUC&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref>]]

The gospel accounts differ on various elements of the trials.{{sfn|Bromiley|1988|pp=1050<U+2013>1052}} In, [[s:Bible (American Standard)/Matthew#26:57|Matthew 26:57]],
[[s:Bible (American Standard)/Mark#14:53|Mark 14:53]] and [[s:Bible (American Standard)/Luke#22:54|Luke 22:54]] Jesus was taken to the high priest's house where he was mocked and beaten that night. The next day, early in the morning, the chief priests and scribes lead Jesus away into their council.{{sfn|Evans|2003|pp=487-500}}{{sfn|Blomberg|2009|pp=396<U+2013>400}}<ref name=Holman608 /><ref>[[s:Bible (American Standard)/Matthew#27:1|Matthew 27:1]], [[s:Bible (American Standard)/Mark#15:1|Mark 15:1]], [[s:Bible (American Standard)/Luke#22:66|22:66]]</ref> In [[s:Bible (American Standard)/John#18:12|John 18:12<U+2013>14]], however, Jesus is first taken to [[Annas]], the father-in-law of Caiaphas, and then to Caiaphas.{{sfn|Evans|2003|pp=487-500}}{{sfn|Blomberg|2009|pp=396<U+2013>400}}<ref name=Holman608 /> All four gospels include the ''[[Denial of Peter]]'' narrative, where Peter denies knowing Jesus three times, at which point the rooster crows as predicted by Jesus.{{sfn|Blomberg|2009|pp=396<U+2013>400}}{{sfn|Bromiley|1988|p=105}}

In the gospel accounts Jesus speaks very little, mounts no defense and gives very infrequent and indirect answers to the questions of the priests, prompting an officer to slap him. In [[s:Bible (American Standard)/Matthew#26:62|Matthew 26:62]] the lack of response from Jesus prompts the high priest to ask him: "Answerest thou nothing?"{{sfn|Evans|2003|pp=487-500}}{{sfn|Blomberg|2009|pp=396<U+2013>400}}<ref name=Holman608 /><ref>[[s:Bible (American Standard)/Matthew#26:67|Matthew 26:67]] [[s:Bible (American Standard)/Mark#14:65|Mark 14:65]] [[s:Bible (American Standard)/Luke#22:63|Luke 22:63<U+2013>65]] [[s:Bible (American Standard)/John#18:22|John 18:22]]</ref> In [[s:Bible (American Standard)/Mark#14:61|Mark 14:61]] the high priest then asked Jesus: "Are you the Christ, the Son of the Blessed?" And Jesus said, "I am"<U+2014>at which point the high priest tore his own robe in anger and accused Jesus of blasphemy. In [[s:Bible (American Standard)/Luke#22:70|Luke 22:70]] when asked: "Are you then the Son of God?" Jesus answers: "You say that I am" affirming the title [[Son of God]].{{sfn|Evans|2003|pp=487-500}}{{sfn|Blomberg|2009|pp=396<U+2013>400}}<ref name=Holman608 /><ref>{{cite book|title=Luke's presentation of Jesus: a christology|first=Robert F.|last= O'Toole|year= 2004| isbn= 88-7653-625-6 |page= 166}}</ref>

Taking Jesus to [[Pilate's Court]], the Jewish elders ask [[Pontius Pilate]] to judge and condemn Jesus<U+2014>accusing him of claiming to be the [[Jesus, King of the Jews|King of the Jews]].<ref name=Holman608 /> In [[s:Bible (American Standard)/Luke#23:7|Luke 23:7<U+2013>15]] Pilate realizes that Jesus is a Galilean, and is thus under the jurisdiction of [[Herod Antipas]].{{sfn|Niswonger|1992|p=172}}{{sfn|Majern<U+00ED>k|Ponessa|Manhardt|2005|p=181}}
<ref>{{cite book|title=The Gospel according to Luke|first= Michael|last= Patella|year= 2005| isbn= 0-8146-2862-1| page= 16}}
* {{cite book|title=Luke: The Gospel of Amazement|first= Michael|last= Card|year= 2011| isbn= 978-0-8308-3835-6 |page= 251}}</ref> Pilate sends Jesus to Herod to be tried.{{sfn|Carter|2003|pp=120<U+2013>121}} However, Jesus says almost nothing in response to Herod's questions. Herod and his soldiers mock Jesus, put a gorgeous robe on him, as the King of the Jews, and send him back to Pilate.{{sfn|Niswonger|1992|p=172}} Pilate then calls together the Jewish elders, and says that he has "found no fault in this man."{{sfn|Carter|2003|pp=120<U+2013>121}}

The use of the term king is central in the discussion between Jesus and Pilate. In [[s:Bible (American Standard)/John#18:36|John 18:36]] Jesus states: "My kingdom is not of this world", but does not directly deny being the King of the Jews.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Names of Jesus|first= Stephen J.|last= Binz |year=2004 |isbn= 1-58595-315-6| pages= 81<U+2013>82}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=John|first= H. A.|last= Ironside |year=2006 |isbn= 0-8254-2915-3 |page= 454}}</ref> Pilate then writes "Jesus of Nazareth, King of the Jews" as a sign (abbreviated as [[INRI]] in depictions) to be affixed to the cross of Jesus.{{sfn|Brown|1988|p=93}}

The trial by Pilate is followed by the [[Flagellation of Christ|flagellation]] episode, the soldiers mock Jesus as the King of Jews by putting a purple robe (that signifies royal status) on him, place a [[Crown of Thorns]] on his head, and beat and mistreat him in [[s:Bible (American Standard)/Matthew#27:29|Matthew 27:29<U+2013>30]], [[s:Bible (American Standard)/Mark#15:17|Mark 15:17<U+2013>19]] and [[s:Bible (American Standard)/John#19:2|John 19:2<U+2013>3]].<ref name=Senior>{{cite book|title=The Passion of Jesus in the Gospel of Matthew|first= Donald |last=Senior |year=1985| isbn= 0-89453-460-2 |page= 124}}</ref> Jesus is then sent to Calvary for crucifixion.{{sfn|Evans|2003|pp=487-500}}{{sfn|Blomberg|2009|pp=396<U+2013>400}}<ref name=Holman608 />

==== Crucifixion and burial ====
{{Main |Crucifixion of Jesus|Entombment of Christ}}
{{See also|Sayings of Jesus on the cross|Crucifixion eclipse}}
[[File:Pietro Perugino 040.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Pietro Perugino]]'s depiction of the [[Crucifixion of Jesus|Crucifixion]] as ''[[Stabat Mater (art)|Stabat Mater]]'', 1482]]
Jesus' crucifixion is described in all four canonical gospels, is attested to by other sources of that age, including Josephus and Tacitus, and is regarded as an historical event.<ref name=Funk&Seminar>{{cite book |last=Funk |first=Robert W. |coauthors=[[Jesus Seminar|Seminar, Jesus]] |authorlink=Robert W. Funk| title=The acts of Jesus: the search for the authentic deeds of Jesus |year=1998 |publisher=Harper |location=San Francisco|pages=449<U+2013>495}}</ref><ref name=Crossan1995>{{cite book |last=Crossan|first= John D. |title=Jesus: A Revolutionary Biography |isbn=0-06-061662-8 |year=1995 |publisher=HarperOne |page=145|postscript=. "That he was crucified is as sure as anything historical can ever be, since both Josephus and Tacitus&nbsp;... agree with the Christian accounts on at least that basic fact."}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=The Word in this world|first1= Paul W.|last1= Meyer|first2= John T.|last2= Carroll|year= 2004|isbn= 0-664-22701-5 |page= 112}}</ref>

After the trials, Jesus made his way to [[Calvary]] (the path is traditionally called [[via Dolorosa]]) and the three synoptic gospels indicate that he was assisted by [[Simon of Cyrene]], the Romans compelling him to do so.{{sfn|Evans|2003|pp=509-520}}{{sfn|K<U+00F6>stenberger|Kellum|Quarles|2009|pp=211<U+2013>214}} In [[s:Bible (American Standard)/Luke#23:27|Luke 23:27<U+2013>28]] Jesus tells the women in the multitude of people following him not to cry for him but for themselves and their children.{{sfn|Evans|2003|pp=509-520}} Once at Calvary (Golgotha), Jesus was offered wine mixed with gall to drink&nbsp;<U+2013> usually offered as a form of painkiller. Matthew's and Mark's gospels state that he refused this.{{sfn|Evans|2003|pp=509-520}}{{sfn|K<U+00F6>stenberger|Kellum|Quarles|2009|pp=211<U+2013>214}}

The soldiers then crucified Jesus and cast lots for his clothes. Above Jesus' head on the cross was the inscription [[Jesus, King of the Jews|King of the Jews]], and the soldiers and those passing by mocked him about the title. Jesus was crucified between two convicted thieves, one of whom rebuked Jesus, while the other defended him.{{sfn|Evans|2003|pp=509-520}}{{sfn|Doninger|p=271}}

The Roman soldiers did not break Jesus' legs, as they did to the other two men crucified (breaking the legs hastened the crucifixion process), as Jesus was dead already. One of the soldiers traditionally known as [[Saint Longinus]], pierced the side of Jesus with a lance and water flowed out.{{sfn|Doninger|p=271}} In [[s:Bible (American Standard)/Mark#15:39|Mark 15:39]], impressed by the events, the Roman [[centurion]] calls Jesus the [[Son of God]].{{sfn|Evans|2003|pp=509-520}}{{sfn|K<U+00F6>stenberger|Kellum|Quarles|2009|pp=211<U+2013>214}}<ref>{{cite book|title=The Gospel according to Mark|first= George|last= Martin |year=2005 |isbn= 0-8294-1970-5 |page= 440}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Mark|first= Allen |last=Black |year=1995| isbn= 0-89900-629-9 |page= 280}}</ref>

Following Jesus' death on Friday, [[Joseph of Arimathea]] asked the permission of Pilate to remove the body. The body was [[Descent from the Cross|removed from the cross]], was wrapped in a clean cloth and buried in a new [[Sepulchre|rock-hewn tomb]], with the assistance of [[Nicodemus]].{{sfn|Evans|2003|pp=509-520}} In [[s:Bible (American Standard)/Matthew#27:62|Matthew 27:62<U+2013>66]] the Jews go to Pilate the day after the crucifixion and ask for guards for the tomb and also seal the tomb with a stone as well as the guard, to be sure the body remains there.{{sfn|Evans|2003|pp=509-520}}{{sfn|Morris|1992|page=727}}

=== Resurrection and ascension ===
{{Main|Resurrection of Jesus|Resurrection appearances of Jesus|Ascension of Jesus}}
{{See also|Empty tomb|Great Commission|Second Coming|Resurrection of Jesus in Christian art|Ascension of Jesus in Christian art}}
[[File:IVANOV YAV HRISTA MARI1.jpg|left|thumb|Mary Magdalene's encounter with Jesus after his resurrection, depicted by [[Alexander Andreyevich Ivanov]] in 1835]]
The New Testament accounts of the [[Resurrection of Jesus|resurrection]] and [[Ascension of Jesus|ascension]] of Jesus, state that the first day of the week after the crucifixion (typically interpreted as a Sunday), his followers encounter him risen from the dead, after his tomb is discovered to be empty.{{sfn|Evans|2003|pp=521<U+2013>530}}<ref>[[s:Bible (American Standard)/Matthew#28:1|Matthew 28:1]], [[s:Bible (American Standard)/Mark#16:9|Mark 16:9]], [[s:Bible (American Standard)/Luke#24:1|Luke 24:1]] and [[s:Bible (American Standard)/John#20:1|John 20:1]]</ref>{{sfn|Cox|2007|pp=216<U+2013>226}} The resurrected Jesus appears to them that day and a number of times thereafter, delivers sermons and [[Great Commission|commissions them]], before ascending to Heaven.{{sfn|Evans|2003|pp=521<U+2013>530}}{{sfn|Cox|2007|pp=216<U+2013>226}} When the tomb is discovered empty ([[s:Bible (American Standard)/Matthew#28:5|Matthew 28:5]], [[s:Bible (American Standard)/Mark#16:5|Mark 16:5]], [[s:Bible (American Standard)/Luke#24:4|Luke 24:4]] and [[s:Bible (American Standard)/John#20:12|John 20:12]]) his followers arrive there early in the morning meet either one or two beings (either men or angels) dressed in bright robes who appear in or near the tomb.{{sfn|Evans|2003|pp=521<U+2013>530}}{{sfn|Cox|2007|pp=216<U+2013>226}} [[s:Bible (American Standard)/Mark#16:9|Mark 16:9]] and [[s:Bible (American Standard)/John#20:15|John 20:15]] indicate that Jesus appeared to [[Mary Magdalene]] first, and [[s:Bible (American Standard)/Luke#16:9|Luke 16:9]] states that she was among the [[Myrrhbearers]].{{sfn|Evans|2003|pp=521<U+2013>530}}{{sfn|Cox|2007|pp=216<U+2013>226}}

After the discovery of the empty tomb, the gospels indicate that Jesus made a series of appearances to the disciples.{{sfn|Evans|2003|pp=521<U+2013>530}} These include the well known [[Doubting Thomas]] episode and the [[Road to Emmaus appearance]] where Jesus meets two disciples. The [[catch of 153 fish]] appearance includes a [[miracles of Jesus|miracle]] at the [[Sea of Galilee]], and thereafter Jesus encourages Peter to serve his followers.{{sfn|Evans|2003|pp=521<U+2013>530}}{{sfn|Cox|2007|pp=216<U+2013>226}} The final post-resurrection appearance in the gospel accounts is when Jesus [[Ascension of Jesus Christ|ascends to Heaven]].{{sfn|Evans|2003|pp=521<U+2013>530}} [[s:Bible (American Standard)/Luke#24:51|Luke 24:51]] states that Jesus "was carried up into heaven". The ascension account is elaborated in [[s:Bible (American Standard)/Acts#1:1|Acts 1:1<U+2013>11]] and mentioned [[s:Bible (American Standard)/1 Timothy#3:16|1 Timothy 3:16]]. In [[s:Bible (American Standard)/Acts#1:1|Acts 1:1<U+2013>9]], forty days after the resurrection, as the disciples look on, "he was taken up; and a cloud received him out of their sight." [[s:Bible (American Standard)/1 Peter#3:22|1 Peter 3:22]] describes Jesus as being on "the right hand of God, having gone into heaven".{{sfn|Evans|2003|pp=521<U+2013>530}}

The [[Acts of the Apostles]] also contain "post-ascension" appearances by Jesus. These include the [[vision (spirituality)|vision]] by [[Saint Stephen|Stephen]] just before his death in [[s:Bible (American Standard)/Acts#7:55|Acts 7:55]],<ref>{{cite book|title=''The Acts of the Apostles'' |last=Frederick F.|first= Bruce| isbn= 978-0-8028-0966-7|year=1990|publisher=Wm. B. Eerdmans Publishing |url=http://books.google.com/books?id=2lN0ibbLOHEC&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false | page= 210}}</ref> and the [[Conversion of Paul|road to Damascus episode]] in which [[Paul the Apostle|Apostle Paul]] is converted to Christianity.<ref name=Wiersbe350 /><ref name=HarringtonActs /> The instruction given to [[Ananias of Damascus|Ananias]] in [[Damascus]] in [[s:Bible (American Standard)/Acts#9:10|Acts 9:10<U+2013>18]] to heal Paul is the last reported conversation with Jesus in the Bible until the [[Book of Revelation]] was written.<ref name=Wiersbe350 >{{cite book|title=The Wiersbe Bible Commentary: The Complete New Testament|first=
Warren W. |last=Wiersbe |year=2007| isbn =978-0-7814-4539-9 |pages= 350<U+2013>352}}</ref><ref name=HarringtonActs >{{cite book|title=The Acts of the Apostles |first1=Luke T.|last1= Johnson| first2=Daniel J.|last2= Harrington|year= 1992| isbn= 978-0-8146-5807-9| pages= 164<U+2013>167}}</ref>

== Historical views ==

=== Existence ===
{{Main|Historicity of Jesus|Chronology of Jesus|Christ myth theory}}
{{See also|Josephus on Jesus|Tacitus on Jesus}}
[[File:WorksJosephus1640TP.jpg|thumb|upright|A 1640 edition of the [[Josephus on Jesus|works of Josephus]], a 1st century [[Roman Jews|Romano-Jewish]] historian who referred to Jesus{{sfn|Blomberg|2009|pp=431<U+2013>436}}<ref name=JospehusM662 >{{cite book|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=kyaoIb6k2ccC&lpg=PP1&dq=isbn%3A0825429242&pg=PA663#v=onepage&q=%22few%20have%20doubted%22&f=false|title=The new complete works of Josephus|first1= Flavius|last1= Josephus|first2= William|last2= Whiston|first3= Paul L.|last3= Maier |isbn= 0-8254-2924-2 |pages= 662<U+2013>663}}</ref>]]

The Christian gospels were written primarily as theological documents rather than historical chronicles.<ref name=Wiarda75 /><ref name=Turner613 /><ref name=BCCrossan21 >{{cite book|title=Birth of Christianity|first= John D. |last=Crossan |year=1999 |isbn= 0-567-08668-2 |page= 21}}</ref> However, the question of the existence of Jesus as a historical figure should be distinguished from discussions about the historicity of specific episodes in the gospels, the chronology they present, or theological issues regarding his divinity.{{sfn|Powell|1998|pp=168<U+2013>173}} A number of historical non-Christian documents, such as Jewish and [[Greco-Roman]] sources, have been used in historical analyses of the existence of Jesus.{{sfn|Blomberg|2009|pp=431<U+2013>436}}

Virtually all scholars of antiquity agree that [[Historicity of Jesus|Jesus existed]] and regard events such as his baptism and his crucifixion as historical.{{sfn|Dunn|2003|p=339}}<ref name=Existence /><ref>{{harvnb|Brown|1994|p= 964}}
* {{harvnb|Dunn| 2003| p= 142}}</ref>{{sfn|Stanton|2002|p=145|ps=: "Today nearly all historians, whether Christians or not, accept that Jesus existed."}}{{sfn|Bockmuehl|2001|pp=123<U+2013>124}} [[Robert E. Van Voorst]] states that the idea of the non-historicity of the existence of Jesus has always been controversial, and has consistently failed to convince scholars of many disciplines, and that classical historians, as well as biblical scholars now regard it as effectively refuted.{{sfn|Van Voorst|2000|p=16|ps=. [[Robert E. Van Voorst]] states that biblical scholars and classical historians regard theories of non-existence of Jesus as effectively refuted.}} Referring to the theories of non-existence of Jesus, [[Richard A. Burridge]] states: "I have to say that I do not know any respectable critical scholar who says that any more."{{sfn|Burridge|Gould|2004|p=34}}

Separate non-Christian sources used to establish the historical existence of Jesus include the works of 1st century Roman historians [[Josephus]] and [[Tacitus]].{{sfn|Blomberg|2009|pp=431<U+2013>436}}{{sfn|Van Voorst|2000|pp=39<U+2013>53}} Josephus scholar [[Louis H. Feldman]] has stated that "few have doubted the genuineness" of Josephus' reference to Jesus in [[s:The Antiquities of the Jews/Book XX#Chapter 9|Antiquities 20, 9, 1]] and it is only disputed by a small number of scholars.<ref name=JospehusM662 /><ref>{{cite book|title=Josephus XX|first=Louis H. |last=Feldman|year= 1965| isbn= 0-674-99502-3 |page= 496}}
* {{harvnb|Van Voorst|2000| p= 83}}
* {{cite book|first1=Flavius |last1=Josephus|last2= Maier|first2= Paul L.|year=1995|title= Josephus, the essential works: a condensation of Jewish antiquities and The Jewish war| isbn= 978-0-8254-3260-6 |pages= 284<U+2013>285}}</ref> [[Bart D. Ehrman]] states that the existence of Jesus and his crucifixion by the Romans is attested to by a wide range of sources, including Josephus and Tacitus.<ref>{{cite book|title=The New Testament: A Historical Introduction to the Early Christian Writings| first=Bart D.|last= Ehrman|year= 1999| isbn= 0-19-512639-4 |page= 248}}</ref>

The historical existence of Jesus as a person is a separate issue from any religious discussions about [[God the Son|his divinity]], or the theological issues relating to [[Hypostatic union|his nature]] as man or God.{{sfn|Pannenberg|1968|p=316}} Leading scientific atheist [[Richard Dawkins]] does not deny the existence of Jesus, although he dismisses the reliability of the gospel accounts.<ref name=dawkings122>{{cite book|title=The God Delusion|first= Richard |last=Dawkins|year= 2006| isbn= 0-618-68000-4 |page= 122}}</ref> This position is also held by leading critic [[G. A. Wells]], who used to argue that Jesus never existed, but has since changed his views and no longer rejects it.{{sfn|Houlden|2003|p=660}}{{sfn|Wells|pp=49-50|ps=. "In my first books on Jesus, I argued that the gospel Jesus is an entirely mythical expansion of the Jesus of the early epistles. The summary of the argument of ''The Jesus Legend'' (1996) and ''The Jesus Myth'' (199a) given in this section of the present work makes it clear that I no longer maintain this position&nbsp;... My present standpoint is: this complex is not all post-Pauline (Q, or at any rate parts of it, may well be as early as ca. A.D. 50); and if I am right, against Doherty and Price - it is not all mythical."}}

In antiquity, the existence of Jesus was never denied by those who opposed Christianity, and neither [[pagan]]s nor Jews questioned his existence.{{sfn|Rahner|2004|pp=730-731}}{{sfn|Van Voorst|2000|p=15}} Although in [[Dialogue with Trypho]], the second century Christian writer [[Justin Martyr]] wrote of a discussion about "Christ" with Trypho, most scholars agree that Trypho is a fictional character invented by Justin for his literary apologetic goals.<ref>{{cite book|title=Exploring Jewish Literature of the Second Temple Period| first= Larry R.|last= Helyer |year=2002| isbn= 0-8308-2678-5 |page= 493}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Jewish Responses To Early Christians| first= Claudia |last=Setzer |year= 1994| isbn= 0-8006-2680-X |page= 215}}</ref><ref>In [https://en.m.wikisource.org/wiki/Ante-Nicene_Fathers/Volume_I/JUSTIN_MARTYR/Dialogue_with_Trypho/Chapter_VIII Chapter VIII] Trypho's statement: "But Christ<U+2014>if He has indeed been born, and exists anywhere<U+2014>is unknown, and does not even know Himself" refers to Christ, which Trypho (as other Jews) still awaited. Justin styled the conversation on [[s:Bible (American Standard)/John#7:27|John 7:27]], with Trypho objecting to Jesus (who was from Galillee) being Christ given that the origins of Jesus were known, but those for Christ could not be, as the Pharisees said of Jesus in John 7:27: "we know this man whence he is: but when the Christ cometh, no one knoweth whence he is." 
* {{cite book|title=Testimony of the Beloved Disciple: The Narrative, History, and Theology in the Gospel of John|first= Richard|last= Bauckham |year= 2007| isbn= 0-8010-3485-X| page= 232}}
* {{harvnb|Cook|Evans|2003|p= 285}}
* {{cite book|title=The Gospel According to John: An Introduction and Commentary|first= Colin G.|last= Kruse |year= 2004| isbn= 0-8028-2771-3 |page= 188}}
* {{cite book|title=The Gospel of John: A Commentary|first= Frederick D. |last= Bruner |year= 2012|isbn= 0-8028-6635-2 |page= 485}}</ref> While theological differences existed among early Christians regarding the nature of Jesus (e.g. [[monophysitism]], [[miaphysitism]], [[Docetism]], [[Nestorianism]], etc.) these were debates in Christian theology, not about the historical existence of Jesus.<ref>{{cite book|first1=Ed |last1=Hindson|first2= Ergun |last2=Caner|title= The Popular Encyclopedia of Apologetics: Surveying the Evidence for The Truth of Christianity| page= 179 |publisher=Harvest House Publishers|year= 2008| isbn= 978-0-7369-2084-1}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=The Oxford handbook of early Christian studies| first1=Susan A.|last1= Harvey|first2= David G.|last2= Hunter |year=2008 |isbn= 0-19-927156-9 |page= 378}}</ref> The [[Christ myth theory]] appeared in the 18th and 19th centuries, and was debated during the 20th century.<ref>{{cite book|title=A theory of primitive Christian religion|first= Gerd|last= Theissen|year= 2003 |isbn= 0-334-02913-9 |pages= 23<U+2013>27}}
* {{cite book|title=The historical Jesus: ancient evidence for the life of Christ|authorlink= Gary Habermas|last=Habermas|first=Gary|year= 1996 |isbn= 0-89900-732-5 |pages= 27<U+2013>31, 47<U+2013>51}}
* {{harvnb|Van Voorst|2000| pp= 7<U+2013>8}}</ref> Supporters of the Christ myth theory point to the lack of any known written references to Jesus during his lifetime and the relative scarcity of non-Christian references to him in the 1st century, and dispute the veracity of the existing accounts of him.{{sfn|Eddy|Boyd|2007|p=162}}

Since the 20th century scholars such as [[George Albert Wells|G. A. Wells]], [[Robert M. Price]] and Thomas Brodie have presented various (and at times differing) arguments to support the Christ myth theory; the most thorough analysis being by G. A. Wells.<ref>{{cite book|first=Thomas L.|last= Brodie |title=Beyond the Quest for the Historical Jesus: Memoir of a Discovery|publisher= Sheffield Phoenix Press|year= 2012| isbn= 978-1-907534-58-4}}
* {{cite encyclopedia|last=Wells|first= G. A. |title=Jesus, Historicity of|editor-first= Tom |editor-last=Flynn |encyclopedia=The New Encyclopedia of Disbelief|publisher= Prometheus|year= 2007| page= 446}}
* {{harvnb|Stanton|2002|p=143}}
* {{harvnb|Eddy|Boyd|2007|pp=24<U+2013>27}}</ref> But Wells' book ''[[Did Jesus Exist?]]'' was criticized by [[James D.G. Dunn]] in his book ''The Evidence for Jesus''.<ref>{{cite book|first=James D.G.|last= Dunn|year= 1985|title= The Evidence for Jesus| isbn= 0-664-24698-2| page= 29}}</ref> Wells then changed his stance on issue and accepted that the [[Q source]] refers to "a preacher who existed", but still maintains that the New Testament accounts of the preacher's life are mostly fiction.{{sfn|Wells|2004|pp=50-52}}{{sfn|Houlden|2003|p=660}}{{sfn|Van Voorst|2000|p=14}}{{sfn|McClymond|2004|p= 163}} [[Robert E. Van Voorst|Robert Van Voorst]] and separately [[Michael Grant (author)|Michael Grant]] state that biblical scholars and classical historians now regard theories of non-existence of Jesus as effectively refuted.{{sfn|Van Voorst|2000|p=16|ps=. [[Robert E. Van Voorst]] states that biblical scholars and classical historians regard theories of non-existence of Jesus as effectively refuted.}}{{sfn|Grant|1977|p=200|ps=. [[Michael Grant (author)|Michael Grant]] (a [[classicist]]) states that "In recent years, 'no serious scholar has ventured to postulate the non historicity of Jesus' or at any rate very few, and they have not succeeded in disposing of the much stronger, indeed very abundant, evidence to the contrary."}}{{sfn|Bockmuehl|2001|pp=141<U+2013>144}}

===Ancient sources and archeology===
{{See also|Jesus and archaeology}}
[[File:Kapernaum Synagoga.jpg|thumb|The ancient [[synagogue]] at [[Capernaum]]]]
Professor [[Bart Ehrman]] states that "Jesus almost certainly did exist", and the [[arguments from ignorance]] that there is no physical or archeological evidence of Jesus nor any writings from him are "not very good arguments, even though they sound good, as there is no such evidence of "nearly ''anyone'' who lived in the first century".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.religiondispatches.org/books/atheologies/5890/inventing_jesus__an_interview_with_bart_ehrman/|title= Inventing Jesus: An Interview with Bart Ehrman | publisher= Religion Dispatches}}</ref><ref name=EhrmanDid29>{{cite book|last=Ehrman |first= Bart |year=2012|title= Did Jesus Exist?| isbn= 978-0-06-220460-8| page= 29}}</ref> Professor Teresa Okure states that in a global cultural context the existence of historical figures are established by the analysis of later references to them rather than by contemporary relics and remnants.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|last=Teresa|first= Okure |title=Historical Jesus Research in Global Cultural Context|encyclopedia=Handbook for the Study of the Historical Jesus|editor-first1= Tom |editor-last1=Holmen| editor-first2= Stanley E.|editor-last2= Porter |year= 2011| isbn= 90-04-16372-7 |pages= 953<U+2013>954}}</ref> Ehrman states that the view that Jesus had an immense impact on the society of his day, and hence one might have expected contemporary accounts of his deeds is not even close to correct and although Jesus had a large impact on future generations, his impact on the society of his time was "practically nil".{{sfn|Ehrman|1999|p= 56|ps=: "If we look at the historical record itself - and for the historian there is nothing else to look at - it appears that whatever his influence on subsequent generations, Jesus' impact on society in the first century was practically nil."}}

In responding to [[G. A. Wells]]' previous [[arguments from silence]] that the lack of the contemporary references implies that Jesus did not exist (Wells no longer adheres to the non-existence hypothesis{{sfn|Wells|2004|pp=50-52}}), [[Robert Van Voorst]] stated that such arguments are "specially perilous" as every good student of history knows.{{sfn|Van Voorst|2000|p= 14|ps=: "As every good student of history knows, it is wrong to suppose that what is unmentioned or undetailed did not exist&nbsp;... Arguments from silence about ancient times here about the supposed lack of biblical or extra-biblical references to Jesus are specially perilous."}} An example of such argument is that although [[Philo]] criticized the brutality of Pontius Pilate in ''Embassy to Gaius'' (c. 40 AD), he did not name Jesus as an example of Pilate's cruelty.{{sfn|Van Voorst|2000|pp=130-132|ps=: "A fourth main conclusion on Jewish sources is that they, like the classical writers, do not treat Jesus independently, but see him through Christianity. As we stated above, Philo does not mention Jesus. While arguing from silence is always difficult, a plausible explanation for this is that he never mentions Christianity, so he has no need to mention its founder (if he even knew of him at all)."}} He adds that a possible explanation is that Philo never mentions Christians at all, so he had no need to mention their founder, given that Jewish literature (like early Roman references) only saw Jesus through Christianity and did not treat him independently.{{sfn|Van Voorst|2000|pp=130-132}} Philo was also silent on the reaction of the Jewish [[Zealotry|Zealots]] to the death of Gaius, perhaps because the theme of ''Embassy to Gaius'' was providence for Israel.<ref>{{cite book|title=Jesus and the Zealots : A Study of the Political Factor in Primitive Christianity|first=  S. G.|last= Brandon |year=1967 |isbn= 0-684-31010-4 |page= 87}}</ref> Bernard Green states that Philo's silence on some comparative aspects of the Jewish communities in Rome and Alexandria (e.g. levels of autonomy and turbulence) was deliberate, given the conciliatory nature of his mission to Gauis.<ref>{{cite book|title=Christianity in Ancient Rome|first= Bernard|last= Green |year=2010| isbn= 0-567-03250-7|publisher= T&T Clark |pages= 19<U+2013>20}}</ref> According to [[Eusebius]] (''[[Church History (Eusebius)|Hist Eccl]]'' II.17) Philo may have become familiar with Christian practices on a subsequent visit to Rome during the reign of [[Claudius]] (41 to 54 AD/CE).<ref>{{cite book|title=Constantine and Eusebius|first= Timothy D. |last=Barnes |year= 2006| isbn= 0-674-16531-4 |publisher=Harvard University Press| page= 130}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Aspects of Roman History|first=Mark E.|last= Davies |year=2010 |isbn= 0-415-49694-2 |page= 79}}</ref> 

In a broad context, [[arguments from silence]] fail unless a fact is known to the author and is important enough and relevant enough to be mentioned in the context of a document.<ref>{{cite book|title=From Reliable Sources: An Introduction to Historical Methods|first1= Martha C. |last1=Howell |first2= Walter |last2=Prevenier |year= 2001| isbn= 0-8014-8560-6 |publisher=Cornell University Press| pages= 73<U+2013>74 |quote=Another difficulty with argument from silence is that historians cannot assume that an observer of a particular fact would have automatically recorded that fact. Authors observe all kinds of events but only record those that seem important to them.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Research Methodology in History|first= Krishnaji |last=Chitnis |year=2006|isbn= 81-7156-121-7 |page= 56}}</ref> Van Voorst states that the [[Historiography|historical interpretation]] of events was not an "instant analysis" as in modern society but involved time lags and Roman sources came to consider Jesus only when the growth of Christianity came to be seen as a threat to Rome, and given that they viewed Christianity as a "superstition" they had little interest in its origins.{{sfn|Van Voorst|2000|p=70}} [[Timothy Barnes]] states that at the turn of the first century, there was only a low level of interest in and awareness of Christians within the [[Roman Empire]], resulting in the lack of any discernible mention of them by Roman authors such as [[Martial]] and [[Juvenal]].<ref>{{cite encyclopedia| first=Timothy |last=Barnes|title=Pagan Perceptions of Christianity|encyclopedia= Early Christianity: Origins and  Evolution to Ad 600|editor-first1=Ian |editor-last=Hazlett |year= 1991| isbn= 0-687-11444-6 |page= 232|quote= Most inhabitants of the Roman Empire in A.D. 100 were either unaware of or uninterested in the Christians in their midst. Even in Rome, where there had certainly been Christians since the reign of [[Claudius]], the varied epigrams of [[Martial]] and the satires of [[Juvenal]] make no identifiable allusion to the new religion, though both authors deride Jews and Judaism.}}</ref> [[Louis Feldman]] states that one reason first century historian [[Josephus]] refers to Jesus in the ''[[Antiquities of the Jews]]'' (written c. 93 AD) but not in the ''[[Jewish Wars]]'' (written c. 75 AD) may be that in the twenty-year gap between the two works the growth of Christianity had made it a more important topic.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|last=Feldman|first= Louis H. |year=1984|title=Flavius Josephus Revisited: The Man, his Writings and his Significance| editor-last1= Temporini|editor-first1= Hildegard|editor-last2= Haase|editor-first2= Wolfgang|encyclopedia= Aufstieg und Niedergang der r<U+00F6>mischen Welt, Part 2 |isbn= 3-11-009522-X |page= 826 |quote=Alternatively, we may conclude that Christians had become more important during the interval between the time of the composition of the 'War' and that of the 'Antiquities'.}}</ref>

In the broad historical context, a number of scholars caution against the use of [[arguments from ignorance]] and consider them generally inconclusive or [[logical fallacy|fallacious]], given their reliance on "negative evidence".<ref>{{cite book|title=A Systematic Theory of Argumentation|first1= Frans H. |last1=van Eemeren |first2= Rob |last2=Grootendorst|year= 2003| isbn= 0-521-53772-X| publisher= Cambridge University Press |page= 182}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=The Blackwell Dictionary of Western Philosophy|first1= Nicholas |last1=Bunnin |first2=Jiyuan |last2=Yu |year= 2009| isbn= 1-4051-9112-0 |page= 48}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Arguments from Ignorance|first= Douglas |last=Walton |year= 2009| isbn= 0-271-01475-X|publisher= Penn State Press |pages= 1<U+2013>4}}</ref> [[Doug Walton|Douglas Walton]] states that arguments from ignorance can only lead to sound conclusions in cases where we can assume that our "[[Completeness|knowledge-base is complete]]".<ref>{{cite journal|first=Douglas|last= Walton|title=Nonfallacious arguments from ignorance| journal=[[American Philosophical Quarterly]] |volume=29|issue= 4|month=October|year= 1992| pages= 381<U+2013>387}}</ref> Despite the lack of specific [[archaeology|archaeological]] remnants directly attributed to Jesus, the 21st century has witnessed an increase in scholarly interest in the integrated use of archaeology as an additional research component in arriving at a better understanding of the historical background of Jesus by illuminating the socio-economic and political background of his age.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|first=Jonathan L.|last= Reed |title= Archaeological contributions to the study of Jesus and the Gospels|encyclopedia=The Historical Jesus in Context| editor-first=Jill |editor-last=Levine|publisher= Princeton University Press |year=2006 |isbn= 978-0-691-00992-6 |pages= 40<U+2013>47}}
* {{harvnb|Reed |2002| pp= xi<U+2013>xii}}
* {{cite book|author=Craig A. Evans|title=The Archaeological Evidence For Jesus|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/craig-a-evans/archaeological-evidence-for-jesus_b_1370995.html|date=Mar 26, 2012|publisher=The Huffington Post}}</ref><ref name=Charlesworth11 >{{cite encyclopedia|title=Jesus Research and Archaeology: A New Perspective|first= James H.|last= Charlesworth |encyclopedia=Jesus and archaeology|editor-first= James H.|editor-last= Charlesworth |year=2006 |isbn= 0-8028-4880-X |pages=11<U+2013>15}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=What are they saying about the historical Jesus?|first=David B. |last=Gowler |year=2007| isbn= 0-8091-4445-X| page= 102}}
* {{cite book|author=Craig A. Evans|url=http://books.google.com/?id=_DGjygAACAAJ&dq=Jesus+and+His+World|title=Jesus and His World: The Archaeological Evidence |date=Mar 16, 2012|publisher=[[Westminster John Knox Press]]|isbn=0-664-23413-5}}</ref> [[James Charlesworth]] states that few modern scholars now want to overlook the archaeological discoveries that clarify the nature of life in Galilee and Judea during the time of Jesus.<ref name=Charlesworth11 /> Jonathan Reed states that chief contribution of archaeology to the study of the historical Jesus is the reconstruction of his social world.{{sfn|Reed|2002|p=18}}

=== Historicity of events ===

{{Main|Historicity of Jesus}}
{{see also|Cultural and historical background of Jesus|History of the Jews in the Roman Empire|Higher criticism|Textual criticism|Historical reliability of the Gospels}}
Modern scholars consider the [[baptism of Jesus]] and [[Crucifixion of Jesus|his crucifixion]] to be the two historically certain facts about him, [[James Dunn (theologian)|James Dunn]] stating that these "two facts in the life of Jesus command almost universal assent".{{sfn|Dunn|2003|p=339}} Dunn states that these two facts "rank so high on the 'almost impossible to doubt or deny' scale of historical facts" that they are often the starting points for the study of the historical Jesus.{{sfn|Dunn|2003|p=339}} [[Bart Ehrman]] states that the crucifixion of Jesus on the orders of [[Pontius Pilate]] is the most certain element about him.<ref>{{cite book|title=A Brief Introduction to the New Testament|first= Bart D.|last= Ehrman|year= 2008| isbn= 0-19-536934-3 |page= 136}}</ref> [[John Dominic Crossan]] states that the crucifixion of Jesus is as certain as any historical fact can be.<ref name=Crossan1995/>

[[Craig Blomberg]] states that most scholars in the third [[quest for the historical Jesus]] consider the crucifixion indisputable.{{sfn|Blomberg|2009|pp=211<U+2013>214}} Although scholars agree on the historicity of the crucifixion, they differ on the reason and context for it. Both [[E.P. Sanders]] and [[Paula Fredriksen]] support the historicity of the crucifixion, but contend that Jesus did not foretell of his own crucifixion, and that his prediction of the crucifixion is a Christian story.<ref name=Ernest125/> [[Geza Vermes]] also views the crucifixion a historical event but provides his own explanation and background for it.<ref name=Ernest125>{{cite book |title=A Century of Theological and Religious Studies in Britain, 1902<U+2013>2002| first= Ernest |last=Nicholson |year=2004| isbn= 0-19-726305-4 |pages= 125<U+2013>126}}</ref> [[John P. Meier]] views the crucifixion of Jesus as historical fact and states that based on the ''[[criterion of embarrassment]]'' Christians would not have invented the painful death of their leader.{{sfn|Meier|2006|pp=126<U+2013>128}} Meier states that a number of other criteria, such as the criterion of ''[[Criterion of multiple attestation|multiple attestation]]'' (confirmation by more than one source), the ''criterion of coherence'' (that it fits with other historical elements) and the ''criterion of rejection'' (that it is not disputed by ancient sources) help establish the crucifixion of Jesus as a historical event.{{sfn|Meier|2006|pp=132<U+2013>136}}

===Portraits of Jesus===
{{Main|Historical Jesus|Quest for the historical Jesus}}
[[Image:P52 recto.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Rylands Library Papyrus P52|P52]], a papyrus fragment from a codex (''c''. 90<U+2013>160), one of the earliest known New Testament manuscripts]]
Although scholars agree on basic historical facts such as the crucifixion of Jesus, the various "portraits of Jesus" they construct often differ from each other, and from the descriptions found in the gospels.{{sfn|K<U+00F6>stenberger|Kellum|Quarles|2009|pp=117<U+2013>125}}<ref>{{harvnb|Sanders |1993| p= 57}}
* {{harvnb|Levine| 2006| pp= 1<U+2013>2}}
* {{harvnb|Ehrman |1999| pp= ix<U+2013>xi}}
* {{harvnb|Dunn| 2003| pp= 125<U+2013>127}}</ref>

Since the 18th century, three separate scholarly [[Quest for the historical Jesus|quests for the historical Jesus]] have taken place, each with distinct characteristics and based on different research criteria, which were often developed during that phase.{{sfn|Witherington|1997|pp=9<U+2013>13}}{{sfn|Powell|1998|pp=19-23}} The second quest which started in 1953 reached a plateau in the 1970s and by 1992 the term third quest had been coined to characterize the new research approaches.<ref>{{harvnb|Van Voorst| 2000| pp=2<U+2013>6}}
* {{harvnb|Theissen|Dagmar |2002| pp= 1<U+2013>6}}
* {{cite book|title=Criteria for Authenticity in Historical-Jesus Research|first= Stanley E.|last= Porter|year= 2004 |isbn= 0-567-04360-6 |pages= 28<U+2013>29}}
* {{cite book|title=John, Jesus, and History, Volume 1: Critical Appraisals of Critical Views|first1= Paul N.|last1= Anderson|first2= Felix |last2=Just |first3= Tom|last3= Thatcher |year= 2007| isbn= 1-58983-293-0 |page= 127}}</ref>

In the third quest, research on the historical Jesus entered a new phase, and although a new emphasis on methods emerged, [[Gerd Theissen]] and [[Dagmar Winter]] stated that by early 21st century due to the fragmentation of the portraits of Jesus no unified picture of Jesus could be attained at all.{{sfn|Theissen|Winter|2002|p=5}} Echoing the same scenario, [[Ben Witherington III|Ben Witherington]] states that "there are now as many portraits of the historical Jesus as there are scholarly painters".{{sfn|Witherington|1997|p=77}}

Thus while there is widespread scholarly agreement on the existence of Jesus, the portraits of Jesus constructed in these quests often differ from each other, and from the image portrayed in the gospel accounts.{{sfn|Theissen|Winter|2002|p=5}}<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |title=Historical Jesus, Quest of the| encyclopedia = Oxford Dictionary of the Christian Church|page= 775}}</ref> The mainstream profiles in the third quest may be grouped together based on their primary theme as ''[[apocalyptic|apocalyptic prophet]]'', ''charismatic healer'', ''[[Cynicism (philosophy)|Cynic philosopher]]'', ''Jewish Messiah'' and an [[egalitarian]] ''prophet of social change''.<ref name=CambHist23>{{cite book|title=The Cambridge History of Christianity, Volume 1 |first1= Margaret M.|last1= Mitchell |first2= Frances M. |last2=Young |year= 2006| isbn= 0-521-81239-9| page= 23}}</ref>{{sfn|K<U+00F6>stenberger|Kellum|Quarles|2009|pp=124<U+2013>125}} There are, however, overlapping attributes among the portraits and pairs of scholars which may differ on some attributes may agree on others.<ref name=CambHist23/>{{sfn|K<U+00F6>stenberger|Kellum|Quarles|2009|pp=124<U+2013>125}}{{sfn|McClymond|2004|pp=16<U+2013>22}}

There are a number of variants to each of these portraits of Jesus, and some scholars reject the basic elements of some portraits, e.g. regarding the "Messiah portrait" scholars such as [[Larry Hurtado]] suggest that Jesus may have never claimed to be the Messiah or the Son of God, and the titles may be later applications.{{sfn|Rausch|2003|p=127}}<ref>{{cite book|title=How On Earth Did Jesus Become a God?| first= Larry W.|last= Hurtado |year= 2005|ISBN= 0802828612 |pages= 36<U+2013>37}}</ref> Other scholars such as [[N. T. Wright]], [[Markus Bockmuehl]] and [[Peter Stuhlmacher]] argue that Jesus had a Messianic mission.{{sfn|Witherington|1997|197}}<ref>{{cite book|title=This Jesus| first= Markus N. A.|last= Bockmuehl |year= 2004| ISBN= 0567082962 |pages= 42<U+2013>44 |url=http://books.google.com/books?id=0FNxuWqMqSIC&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref> Other scholars contend that although Jesus saw himself as the Messiah, he ordered his followers to silence on his [[Messianic secret]].{{sfn|Powell|1999|pp=24<U+2013>25}} Although scholars generally agree that Jesus had "followers", subtle differences exist regarding whether he called and selected his apostles/disciples (as [[John P. Meier]] and N. T. Wright contend), or if he imposed no hierarchy and preached to all in equal terms, as suggested by [[John Dominic Crossan]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Prophet and Teacher: An Introduction to the Historical Jesus|first=William R. |last=Herzog |year= 2005) |ISBN= 0664225284 |pages= 1-6}}</ref>

[[Amy-Jill Levine]] states that there is, however, "a consensus of sorts" on the basic outline of Jesus' life in that most scholars agree that Jesus [[Baptism of Jesus|was baptized]] by [[John the Baptist]], debated Jewish authorities on the subject of God, performed some healings, gathered followers, and [[Crucifixion of Jesus|was crucified]] by Roman prefect [[Pontius Pilate]].{{sfn|Levine|2006|p=4}}

[[Donald Akenson]] has argued that, with very few exceptions, the historians of Yeshua have not followed sound historical practices. He has stated that there is an unhealthy [[argumentum ad populum|reliance on consensus]], for propositions which should otherwise be based on primary sources, or rigorous interpretation. He also holds that some of the criteria being used are faulty.<ref name=Aken539>{{cite book|last1=Akenson|first1=Donald|title=Surpassing wonder: the invention of the Bible and the Talmuds|publisher=University of Chicago Press|year=1998|pages=539<U+2013>555|url=http://books.google.nl/books?id=40E8am9SlwgC&pg=PA540&lpg=PA541#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=2011-Jan-08|quote=...&nbsp;The point I shall argue below is that, the agreed evidentiary practices of the historians of Jesus, despite their best efforts, have not been those of sound historical practice&nbsp;...}}</ref>

=== Language, ethnicity and appearance ===
{{See also|Aramaic of Jesus|Race and appearance of Jesus}}
<!--This section used to be larger, and due to WP:LENGTH limits was trimmed.
Adding more material here will run into WP:LENGTH issues again-->
[[File:CompositeJesus.JPG|thumb|upright|The representation of the ethnicity of Jesus has been influenced by cultural settings.{{sfn|Houlden|2006|pp=63<U+2013>99}}<ref name=Erricker44 />]]
Jesus grew up in [[Galilee]] and much of [[Ministry of Jesus|his ministry]] took place there.<ref name=KGreen442/> The languages spoken in Galilee and [[Judea]] during the 1st century AD/CE include the [[Semitic]] [[Aramaic]] and [[Hebrew]] languages as well as [[Greek language|Greek]], with Aramaic being the predominant language.<ref name=BarrLang >{{cite journal|first=James|last= Barr|title=Which language did Jesus speak| journal=Bulletin of the John Rylands University Library of Manchester|year= 1970|volume= 53|issue=1| pages= 9<U+2013>29 |url=https://www.escholar.manchester.ac.uk/uk-ac-man-scw:1m2973|postscript=. Concerning the language spoken by Jesus, Barr states that Aramaic has the widest support among scholars.}}</ref><ref name=Porter110 >{{cite book|title=Handbook to exegesis of the New Testament|first=Stanley E.|last= Porter|year= 1997| isbn= 90-04-09921-2 |pages= 110<U+2013>112}}</ref> Most scholars agree that during the early part of 1st century AD/CE Aramaic was the mother tongue of virtually all women in Galilee and Judae.<ref>{{cite book |title=Discovering the language of Jesus|first= Douglas |last=Hamp |year=2005 |isbn= 1-59751-017-3 |pages= 3<U+2013>4}}</ref> Most scholars support the theory that Jesus spoke Aramaic and that he may have also spoken Hebrew and Greek.<ref name=BarrLang /><ref name=Porter110 /><ref>{{cite book|title=Jesus in history and myth|first= R. Joseph|last= Hoffmann |year=1986| isbn= 0-87975-332-3 |page= 98}}</ref> [[James D. G. Dunn]] states that there is "substantial consensus" that Jesus gave most of his teachings in Aramaic.{{sfn|Dunn|2003|pp=313<U+2013>315}}

In a review of the state of modern scholarship, [[Amy-Jill Levine]] writes that the entire category of ethnicity is fraught with difficulty. Beyond recognizing that "Jesus was Jewish", rarely does the scholarship address what being "Jewish" means.{{sfn|Levine|2006|p=10}} In the [[New Testament]], written in [[Koine Greek]], Jesus was referred to as an [[Ioudaios]] (i.e. "Judean") on three occasions, although he did not refer to himself as such. These three occasions are (1) by the [[Biblical Magi]] in [[Matthew 2]] who referred to Jesus as [[Jesus, King of the Jews|"basileus ton ioudaion"]]; (2) by the [[Samaritan woman at the well]] in [[John 4]] when Jesus was travelling out of Judea; and (3) by the Romans in all four gospels during [[Passion (Christianity)|the Passion]] who also used the phrase [[Jesus, King of the Jews|"basileus ton ioudaion"]].<ref>{{cite journal|authorlink=John Elliott (historian)|first=John |last=Elliott|journal= Journal for the Study of the Historical Jesus |year=2007|volume= 5|issue= 119}}</ref> According to [[Amy-Jill Levine]], in light of the Holocaust, the Jewishness of Jesus increasingly has been highlighted.

The [[New Testament]] includes no description of the physical appearance of Jesus before his death and its narrative is generally indifferent to racial appearances and does not refer to the features of the people it discusses.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|first=Robin M. |last=Jensen |title=Jesus in Christian art|encyclopedia=The Blackwell Companion to Jesus|editor-first=Delbert|editor-last= Burkett|year= 2010 |isbn= 1-4051-9362-X |pages= 477<U+2013>502}}</ref><ref name=Perkinson30 >{{cite book|title=The likeness of the king: a prehistory of portraiture in late medieval France|first= Stephen |last=Perkinson |year=2009 |isbn= 0-226-65879-1 |page= 30}}</ref><ref name=Kidd48 >{{cite book|title=The forging of races: race and scripture in the Protestant Atlantic world|first= Colin|last= Kidd|year= 2006| isbn =0-521-79324-6 |pages= 48<U+2013>51}}</ref> The synoptic gospels include the account of the [[Transfiguration of Jesus]] during which he was glorified with "his face shining as the sun" but do not provide details of his everyday appearance.<ref name="Nobbs"/><ref name="Barton132"/> The [[Book of Revelation]] describes the features of a glorified Jesus in a vision ([[s:Bible (American Standard)/Revelation#1:13|1:13<U+2013>16]]), but the vision refers to Jesus in heavenly form, after his death and resurrection.<ref>{{cite book|title=Revelation|first= William C.|last= Pender |year=1998 |isbn= 0-664-22858-5 |pages= 14<U+2013>16}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=Revelation 1<U+2013>11 |first=John |last=MacArthur| pages= 37<U+2013>39|year=1999|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=QMAejPLa1CsC&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref>

By the 19th century theories that Jesus was of [[Aryan race|Aryan]] descent, in particular European, were developed and later appealed to those (such as [[Nazi]] theologians) who rejected the Jewishness of Jesus.<ref name=Kidd48 /><ref>{{cite book|title=The Aryan Jesus: Christian theologians and the Bible in Nazi Germany|first= Susannah|last= Heschel |year=2008| isbn= 0-691-12531-7| page= 32}}</ref> These theories usually also include the reasoning that Jesus was Aryan, but have not gained scholarly acceptance.<ref name="Kidd48"/><ref>{{cite book|title=Jesus and the origins of Christianity|first=Maurice |last=Goguel|location= New York |publisher= Harper|year= 1960 |page= 255}}</ref> By the 20th century, theories had also been proposed that Jesus was of [[Black people|black African]] descent, some of them based on the argument that Mary his mother was a descendant of black Jews.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |title=The Black Christ|encyclopedia= The Blackwell Companion to Jesus|editor-first= Delbert|editor-last= Burkett|year= 2010 |isbn= 1-4051-9362-X |pages= 410<U+2013>420}}</ref>

=== Depictions ===
{{Main|Depiction of Jesus}}
<!--This section used to be larger, and due to WP:LENGTH limits was trimmed.
Adding more material here will run into WP:LENGTH issues again-->
[[File:Dura-europos-paralytic.jpg|thumb|upright|A very early image of Jesus, from [[Dura-Europos synagogue|Dura Europos]], c. 235]]
Despite the lack of biblical references or historical records, for two millennia a wide range of depictions of Jesus have appeared, often influenced by cultural settings, political circumstances and theological contexts.{{sfn|Houlden|2006|pp=63<U+2013>99}}<ref name=Erricker44 >{{cite book|title=Teaching Christianity: a world religions approach|first= Clive|last= Erricker|year= 1987 |isbn= 0-7188-2634-5 |page= 44}}</ref><ref name=Perkinson30 /> As in other [[Christian art]], the earliest depictions date to the late 2nd or early 3rd century, and surviving images are primarily found in the [[Catacombs of Rome]].<ref>{{cite book|title=The New Westminster Dictionary of Church History|first= Robert |last=Benedetto|year= 2006| isbn= 0-8264-8011-X |pages= 51<U+2013>53}}</ref>

The [[Byzantine Iconoclasm]] acted as a barrier to developments in the East, but by the 9th century art was permitted again.{{sfn|Houlden|2006|pp=63<U+2013>99}} The [[Transfiguration of Jesus]] was a major theme in the East, and every [[Eastern Orthodox]] monk who had trained in [[icon]] painting had to prove his craft by painting an icon of the Transfiguration.<ref>{{cite book|title=The image of God the Father in Orthodox theology and iconography|first= Steven|last= Bigham|year= 1995 |isbn= 1-879038-15-3 |pages= 226<U+2013>227}}</ref> The [[Renaissance]] brought forth a number of artists who focused on the depictions of Jesus, and after [[Giotto]], [[Fra Angelico]] and others systematically developed uncluttered images.{{sfn|Houlden|2006|pp=63<U+2013>99}} The [[Protestant Reformation]] brought a revival of [[aniconism in Christianity]], but total prohibition was atypical, and Protestant objections to images have tended to reduce since the 16th century. Although large images are generally avoided, few Protestants now object to book illustrations depicting Jesus.<ref>{{cite book|title=Reformation and the Visual Arts|first= Sergiusz|last= Michalski |year= 1993| isbn= 0-415-06512-7 |page= 195}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Light from the Christian East: An Introduction to the Orthodox Tradition|first= James R.|last= Payton|year= 2007| isbn= 0-8308-2594-0 |pages= 178<U+2013>179}}</ref> On the other hand, the use of depictions of Jesus is advocated by the leaders of denominations such as [[Anglicans]] and Catholics<ref name=RWilliams83>{{cite book|title=The Dwelling of the Light: Praying with Icons of Christ|authorlink= Rowan Williams|last=Williams|first=Rowan|year= 2003 |isbn= 1-85311-562-2| page= 83}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vatican.va/holy_father/john_paul_ii/audiences/1997/documents/hf_jp-ii_aud_29101997_en.html|publisher= Vatican website |title= General audience 29 October 1997|accessdate=2013-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.vatican.va/holy_father/benedict_xvi/audiences/2009/documents/hf_ben-xvi_aud_20090506_en.html|publisher= Vatican website |title= General audience 6 May 2009|accessdate=2013-04-20}}</ref> and is a key element of the [[doxology]] of the [[Eastern Orthodox]] tradition.{{sfn|Doninger|p=231}}<ref>{{cite book|title=The Orthodox Christian World|first= Augustine|last= Casiday|year= 2012 |isbn= 0-415-45516-2| page= 447}}</ref>

=== Relics associated with Jesus ===
{{Main|Relics associated with Jesus}}

[[File:Turin plasch.jpg|thumb|upright|left|[[Secondo Pia]]'s 1898 negative of the photograph of the [[Shroud of Turin]], associated with [[Holy Face of Jesus]] devotions]]

A number of [[relic]]s associated with Jesus have been claimed and displayed throughout the history of Christianity. Some people believe in the authenticity of some relics; others doubt the authenticity of various items. For instance, the sixteenth century Catholic theologian [[Erasmus]] wrote sarcastically about the proliferation of relics, and the number of buildings that could have been constructed from the wood claimed to be from the [[True Cross|cross]] used in the [[Crucifixion of Christ]].{{sfn|Dillenberger|1999|p=5}} Similarly, while experts debate whether Christ was crucified with three or with four nails, at least thirty [[Holy Nail]]s continue to be venerated as relics across Europe.<ref>{{CathEncy|wstitle =Holy Nails|title=Holy Nails|first= Herbert|last=Thurston}}</ref>

Some relics, such as purported remnants of the [[Crown of Thorns]], receive only a modest number of pilgrims, others such as the [[Shroud of Turin]] (which is associated with an approved [[Catholic devotion]] to the [[Holy Face of Jesus]]) receive millions of pilgrims, which in recent years have included [[Pope John Paul II]] and [[Pope Benedict XVI]].<ref>{{cite journal |last=Pope John Paul II|authorlink=Pope John Paul II|title=Pope John Paul II's address in Turin Cathedral|url=http://www.vatican.va/holy_father/john_paul_ii/travels/documents/hf_jp-ii_spe_24051998_sindone_en.html|publisher=Holy See|date=1998-05-24}}</ref>

== Religious perspectives ==
{{Main|Religious perspectives on Jesus}}
Apart from his own disciples and followers, the Jews of Jesus' day generally rejected him as the Messiah, as do Jews today. For their part, Christian [[Church Fathers]], [[Ecumenical Council]]s, Reformers, and others have written extensively about Jesus over the centuries. [[Christian sect]]s and [[Christian schisms|schisms]] have often been defined or characterized by competing descriptions of Jesus. Meanwhile, [[Manichaeans]], [[Gnostics]], Muslims, Baha'is, and others have found prominent places for Jesus in their own religious accounts.<ref>{{harvnb|Bockmuehl| 2001| pp= 156<U+2013>157}}
* {{cite book|title=The historical Christ and the Jesus of faith|first= C. Stephen|last= Evans |year=1996|publisher= Oxford University Press| isbn= 0-19-826397-X |page= v}}
* {{cite book|title=The Blackwell Companion to Jesus|last= Delbert|first= Burkett|year= 2010| isbn= 1-4051-9362-X |page= 1}}</ref>

=== Christian views ===
{{Main|Jesus in Christianity|Christology}}
{{see also|Christian denominations}}
{{Christianity|state=collapsed}}
Although Christian views of Jesus vary, it is possible to summarize key elements of the shared beliefs among major denominations based on their [[catechism|catechetical]] or [[Confessionalism (religion)|confessional]] texts.<ref>{{cite book|last=Jackson|first= Gregory L. |title= Catholic, Lutheran, Protestant: a doctrinal comparison|year= 1993 |isbn= 978-0-615-16635-3| pages= 11<U+2013>17}}
* {{cite book|title=The Orthodox Church: An Introduction to Its History, Doctrine|first= John A.|last= McGuckin |year=2010| pages= 6<U+2013>7}}
* {{cite book|title=Basic Christian doctrine|authorlink= John H. Leith|last=Leith|first=John H.|year= 1993 |isbn= 0-664-25192-7 |pages= 1<U+2013>2}}</ref> Christian views of Jesus are derived from various sources, but especially from the [[canonical Gospels]], and New Testament letters, such as the [[Pauline Epistles|Letters of Paul]] and [[Johannine writings]]. These documents outline the key beliefs held by Christians about Jesus, including his [[God the Son|divinity]], [[Hypostatic union|humanity]], and earthly life. Generally speaking, adhering to the Christian faith requires a belief that Jesus is the [[Christ]] and the [[Son of God]]. In the New Testament Jesus indicates that he is the Son of God by calling God his father.<ref name="OneTeacher"/> However, not all [[Christian denominations]] agree on all doctrines, and both [[East<U+2013>West Schism|major and minor differences]] on teachings and beliefs have persisted throughout Christianity for centuries.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|title=Great Schism| encyclopedia = Oxford Dictionary of the Christian Church |publisher= Oxford University Press |year=2005 |isbn= 978-0-19-280290-3}}</ref>

Christians consider Jesus the [[Christ]] and believe that through [[Resurrection of Jesus|his death and resurrection]], humans can be [[reconciliation (theology)|reconciled to God]] and thereby are offered [[Salvation (Christianity)|salvation]] and the promise of [[Eternal life (Christianity)|eternal life]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Oxford Companion to the Bible|first1=Bruce M.|last1= Metzger|first2= Michael D.|last2= Coogan| page= 649| publisher=Oxford University Press| url=http://books.google.com/books?id=Y2KGVuym5OUC&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref> These teachings emphasize that as the willing [[Lamb of God]], Jesus ''chose to'' suffer in [[Calvary]] as a sign of his full obedience to the will of the [[God the Father|Eternal Father]], as an "agent and servant of God".<ref>{{cite book|title=The Christology of the New Testament|first= Oscar |last=Cullmann |year=1959 |isbn= 0-664-24351-7| page= 79}}
* {{cite book|title=The Christology of Anselm of Canterbury|first= D<U+00E1>niel|last= Deme|year= 2004| isbn= 0-7546-3779-4 |pages= 199<U+2013>200}}</ref> The choice Jesus made thus counter-positions him as a the [[new Adam|new and last Adam]], new man of morality and obedience, in contrast to [[Adam and Eve|Adam's disobedience]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Systematic Theology, Volume 2|first= Wolfhart |last=Pannenberg |year=2004 |isbn=0-567-08466-3 |pages= 297<U+2013>303}}</ref>

Most Christians believe that Jesus was both human and the Son of God. While there has been theological debate over the nature of Jesus, [[Trinity|Trinitarian]] Christians generally believe that Jesus is the [[Logos (Christianity)|Logos]], [[Incarnation (Christianity)|God incarnate]], [[God the Son]], and "[[Hypostatic union|true God and true man]]" (or both fully divine and fully human). [[Nontrinitarianism|Nontrinitarian]] Christians reject the notion of the [[Holy Trinity]], do not adhere to the [[ecumenical council]]s and believe that their interpretations of the Bible take precedence over the [[Christian creeds]].<ref>{{cite book|first=Leo D.|last= Davis |title=The First Seven Ecumenical Councils (325<U+2013>787): Their History and Theology|year= 1990 |isbn= 978-0-8146-5616-7 |page= 68}}</ref>

Christians not only attach theological significance to the works of Jesus, but also to his name. Devotions to the [[Holy Name of Jesus]] go back to the [[Early Christianity|earliest days of Christianity]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Outlines of dogmatic theology, Volume 2|first= Sylvester |last=Hunter|year= 2010| isbn= 1-146-98633-5 |page= 443}}</ref>{{sfn|Houlden|2006|p=426}} These devotions and feasts exist both in [[Eastern Christianity|Eastern]] and [[Western Church|Western Christianity]].{{sfn|Houlden|2006|p=426}}

=== Jewish views ===
{{Main|Judaism's view of Jesus}}
{{see also|Jesus in the Talmud}}

[[Judaism]] rejects the idea of Jesus being God, or a person of a Trinity, or a mediator to God. Judaism also holds that Jesus is not the [[Jewish Messianism|Messiah]], arguing that he had not fulfilled the [[Messianic prophecies]] in the [[Tanakh]] nor embodied the personal qualifications of the Messiah. According to Jewish tradition, there were no prophets after [[Malachi]], who delivered his prophesies about 420 BC/BCE.<ref>[[Shraga Simmons|Simmons, Shraga]], "[http://www.aish.com/jewishissues/jewishsociety/Why_Jews_Dont_Believe_In_Jesus.asp Why Jews Do not Believe in Jesus]", Retrieved 2007-04-15; "[http://ohr.edu/ask_db/ask_main.php/2637/Q1/ Why Jews Do not Believe in Jesus]", [[Ohr Somayach, Jerusalem|Ohr Samayach]]&nbsp;<U+2013> ''Ask the Rabbi'', Retrieved 2007-04-15; "[http://www.askmoses.com/qa_detail.html?h=120&o=350 Why do not Jews believe that Jesus was the Messiah?]", [[AskMoses.com]], Retrieved 2007-04-15</ref>

The New Testament states that Jesus was criticized by the Jewish authorities of his time. The [[Pharisee]]s and [[scribe]]s criticized Jesus and his disciples for not observing the Mosaic Law, not washing their hands before eating ({{bibleverse||Mark|7:1<U+2013>23|ESV}}, {{bibleverse||Matthew|15:1<U+2013>20|esv}}), and gathering grain on the Sabbath ({{bibleverse||Mark|2:23<U+2013>3:6|esv}}). Jesus continued to be criticized by Judaism, and in the early 12th century, the [[Mishneh Torah]] (the last established consensus of the Jewish community) called Jesus a "stumbling block" who makes "the majority of the world err to serve a divinity besides God".

The [[Talmud]] includes stories which some consider accounts of [[Jesus in the Talmud]], although there is a spectrum{{sfn|Van Voorst|2000|p=108}} from scholars, such as [[Johann Maier (talmudic scholar)|Maier]] (1978), who considers that only the accounts with the name ''[[Yeshu]]'' {{lang|he|<U+05D9><U+05B5><U+05E9><U+05C1><U+05D5><U+05BC>}} refer to the Christian Jesus, and that these are late redactions, to scholars such as [[Joseph Klausner|Klausner]] (1925), who suggested that accounts related to Jesus in the Talmud may contain traces of the [[historical Jesus]]. However the majority of contemporary historians disregard this material as providing information on the historical Jesus.<ref name = "TM1998">Theissen, Gerd and Annette Merz. The historical Jesus: a comprehensive guide. Fortress Press. 1998. translated from German (1996 edition)</ref> Many contemporary Talmud scholars view these as comments on the relationship between Judaism and Christianity or other sects, rather than comments on the historical Jesus.<ref>Daniel Boyarin, ''Dying for God: Martyrdom and the Making of Christianity and Judaism'' Stanford: Stanford University Press, 1999</ref><ref>Jeffrey Rubenstein ''Rabbinic Stories'' (The Classics of Western Spirituality) New York: The Paulist Press, 2002</ref>

The ''[[Mishneh Torah]]'', an authoritative work of [[Halakha|Jewish law]], provides the last established consensus view of the Jewish community, in ''Hilkhot Melakhim'' 11:10<U+2013>12 that Jesus is a "stumbling block" who makes "the majority of the world err to serve a divinity besides God".<ref>[http://www.mechon-mamre.org/i/e511.htm Hilchot Malachim (laws concerning kings) (Hebrew)]", MechonMamre.org, Retrieved 2007-04-15</ref> According to Conservative Judaism, Jews who believe Jesus is the Messiah have "crossed the line out of the Jewish community".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uscj.org/Messianic_Jews_Not_J5480.html|title=Messianic Jews Are Not Jews|accessdate=2008-01-15|last=Waxman|first=Jonathan|year=2006|publisher=[[United Synagogue of Conservative Judaism]]|quote=Judaism has held that the Mashiach will come and usher in a new era; not that he will proclaim his arrival, die and wait centuries to finish his task. To continue to assert that Jesus was the Mashiach goes against the belief that the Mashiach will transform the world when he does come, not merely hint at a future transformation at some undefined time to come&nbsp;... Judaism rejects the claim that a new covenant was created with Jesus and asserts instead that the chain of Tradition reaching back to Moshe continues to make valid claims on our lives, and serve as more than mere window dressing. |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20080109024012/http://uscj.org/Messianic_Jews_Not_J5480.html <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate =2008-01-09}}</ref> Reform Judaism, the modern progressive movement, states "For us in the Jewish community anyone who claims that Jesus is their savior is no longer a Jew and is an [[apostate]]".<ref>Contemporary American Reform Responsa, #68, "[http://www.faqs.org/faqs/judaism/FAQ/10-Reform/section-15.html Question 18.3.4: Reform's Position On&nbsp;... What is unacceptable practice?]", faqs.org. Retrieved 2007-04-15.</ref>

=== Islamic views ===
{{Main|Jesus in Islam}}
[[File:Medieval Persian manuscript Muhammad leads Abraham Moses Jesus.jpg|thumb|[[Muhammad]] leads Jesus, [[Abraham]], [[Moses]] and others in prayer. Medieval Persian miniature.]]
In [[Islam]], Jesus ({{lang-ar|<U+0639><U+064A><U+0633><U+0649>}} ''{{transl|ar|DIN|<U+02BF><U+012A>s<U+0101>}}''<!--Yas<U+016B><U+02BF> is in Christian contexts, never in Islam called Yas<U+016B><U+02BF>-->) is considered to be a [[Apostle (Islam)|Messenger of God]] and the ''[[Masih]]'' ([[Messiah]]) who was sent to guide the [[Israelites|Children of Israel]] (''ban<U+012B> isr<U+0101>'<U+012B>l'') with a new scripture, the ''[[Gospel (Islam)|Inj<U+012B>l]]'' or [[Gospel]].<ref>{{cite book|title=The Oxford Dictionary of Islam|year=2003|first=John L. |last=Esposito |page= 158|publisher=Oxford University Press| url=http://books.google.com/books?id=E324pQEEQQcC&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref> The belief in Jesus (and all other messengers of God) is required in Islam, and a requirement of being a [[Muslim]]. The [[Quran|Qur'an]] mentions Jesus twenty-five times, more often, by name, than [[Muhammad]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.oxfordislamicstudies.com/article/opr/t125/e1196|title= Jesus, Son of Mary|publisher= Oxford Islamic Studies Online}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.islam101.com/history/people/prophets/jesus/christ_in_islam2.htm|title=Jesus in the Quran|publisher=islam101.com|accessdate=2011-07-08}}</ref>

There is no mention of [[Saint Joseph|Joseph]] in the Quran, but it includes the annunciation to [[Mary (mother of Jesus)|Mary]] ([[Romanization of Arabic|Arabic]]: [[Islamic views of Mary|Maryam]]) by an angel that she is to give birth to Jesus while [[Virgin birth of Jesus|remaining a virgin]], a miraculous event which occurred by the will of [[God in Islam|God]] (Arabic: [[Allah]]).<ref name=RobB32 /><ref name=Peters23 /><ref name=Phyllis558 /> The details of Mary's conception are not discussed during the angelic visit, but elsewhere the Quran (21:91 and 66:12) states that God breathed "His Spirit" into Mary while she was chaste.<ref name=RobB32 /><ref name=Peters23 >{{cite book|title=Islam: A Guide for Jews and Christians|first= F. E.|last= Peters |year=2005 |publisher=Princeton University Press |isbn= 0-691-12233-4| page= 23}}</ref><ref name=Phyllis558 >{{cite book|title=Holy people of the world: a cross-cultural encyclopedia, Volume 1| first=Phyllis G. |last=Jestice |year=2004| isbn= 1-57607-355-6 |pages= 558<U+2013>559}}</ref><ref>{{cite book| title= Encyclopedia of Islam, Vol. VI|page= 629|publisher=Brill|year=1989}}</ref> In Islam, Jesus is called the "Spirit of God" because he was born through the action of the [[Holy Spirit (Islam)|spirit]], but that belief does not include the doctrine of [[Pre-existence of Christ|his pre-existence]], as it does in Christianity.<ref name=RobB32 >{{cite book|title=Christianity, Islam, and the West|first= Robert A.|last= Burns|year= 2011| isbn= 0-7618-5559-9 |page= 32}}</ref>

Numerous other titles are given to Jesus in [[Islamic literature]], the most common being ''al-Mas<U+012B><U+1E25>'' ("the messiah"). Jesus is also, at times, called "Seal of the Israelite Prophets", because, in general Muslim belief, Jesus was the last [[prophet]] sent by [[God]] to guide the Children of Israel. Jesus is seen in Islam as a precursor to Muhammad, and is believed by Muslims to have foretold the latter's coming.<ref name="EoI-Isa"/><ref>{{cite book|title=Comparative Religious Ethics: A Narrative Approach|first1=Darrell J.|last1= Fasching |first2= Dell |last2=deChant|year=2001| page= 241|isbn=978-0-631-20125-0}}</ref> To aid in his ministry to the [[Jews|Jewish]] people, Jesus was given the ability to perform [[miracle]]s, all by the permission of God rather than of his own power.

The Qur'an emphasizes that Jesus was a mortal human being who, like all other prophets, had been divinely chosen to spread God's message. Islamic texts forbid the association of partners with God (''[[Shirk (Islam)|shirk]]''), emphasizing a strict notion of [[monotheism]] (''[[tawhid|tawh<U+012B>d]]''). Like all [[Prophets of Islam|prophets in Islam]], Jesus is considered to have been a ''Muslim'' as he preached that his followers should adopt the "straight path" as commanded by God.<ref name="EoI-Isa">{{cite encyclopedia|title=Isa|encyclopedia= Encyclopedia of Islam, Vol. IV| publisher =Brill|year=1998}}</ref><ref name="EoQ">{{cite encyclopedia|year=2003|encyclopedia=[[Encyclopedia of the Qur'an]]|title= Jesus|editor-first=Jane D.|editor-last= McAuliffe}}</ref>

Islam rejects the [[Christian]] view that Jesus was [[Incarnation (Christianity)|God incarnate]] or the [[Son of God]], that he was ever [[Crucifixion|crucified]] or [[Resurrection of Jesus|resurrected]], or that he ever [[Atonement in Christianity|atoned]] for the sins of mankind. The Qur'an says that Jesus himself never claimed any of these things, and it furthermore indicates that Jesus will deny having ever claimed divinity at the [[Islamic view of the Last Judgment|Last Judgment]], and God will vindicate him (Quran 5:116). According to Muslim traditions, [[Crucifixion of Jesus|Jesus was not crucified]] but instead, he was raised up by God unto the heavens. This "raising" is understood to mean through bodily [[Jesus in Islam#Ascension|ascension]]. Muslims believe that Jesus will return to earth near the [[Last Judgment|day of judgment]] to restore justice.<ref name="EoI-Isa" /><ref name="EoQ" />

==== Ahmadiyya views ====
{{Main|Jesus in Ahmadiyya Islam}}

The [[Ahmadiyya Movement]] believes that Jesus was a mortal man who survived his crucifixion and then died a natural death at the age 120 in [[Kashmir]].<ref name=Ahmad>{{cite web|url=http://www.alislam.org/library/books/jesus-in-india/index.html |title=Jesus in India |publisher=Alislam.org |date= |accessdate=2010-11-19}}</ref><ref name=WebsterAhmad>{{cite book|title=Merriam Webster's Collegiate Encyclopedia|first= Mark A. |last=Stevens |year= 2001| ISBN= 0-87779-017-5 |page= 26}}</ref><ref name=Melton55/><ref name=OCollins169>{{cite book|title=Focus on Jesus|first1=Gerald |last1=O'Collins| first2= Daniel |last2=Kendall |year= 1998| ISBN= 0-85244-360-9 | publisher=Mercer University Press | pages=169<U+2013>171}}</ref> According to [[Mirza Ghulam Ahmad]], the 19th century founder of the Ahmadiyya Movement, Jesus did not die on the cross but fell into a [[Swoon hypothesis|comatose state]] and later regained consciousness after being nursed back to health by the application of [[Aloe]] and [[Myrrh]].<ref name=Ahmad/><ref name="WebsterAhmad"/><ref name=Melton55/> Mainstream Muslims reject Jesus being nursed back after crucifixion and various other Ahmadiyya beliefs; and in some cases (e.g. in Pakistan) consider Ahmadiyya not Muslim.<ref>{{cite book|last=Valentine|first= Simon |year=2008|title=Islam and the Ahmadiyya jama<U+02BB>at: history, belief, practice| publisher=Columbia University Press |ISBN =978-0-231-70094-8| pages= 19 and 59}}</ref>

The Ahmadiyyas believe that after this apparent death and resurrection, Jesus then fled Judea and migrated eastwards to further teach the gospels and is presently buried at [[Roza Bal]] in Kashmir.<ref name=OCollins169/><ref>{{Cite book|last=Rice|first=Edward|title=Eastern Definitions: A Short Encyclopedia of Religions of the Orient|year=1978|publisher=New York|isbn=0-385-08563-X|page=7}}</ref> The Ahmadi reject the notion that Jesus traveled to India before his crucifixion.<ref>{{cite book|title=Jesus in India|first= Mirza G.|last= Ahmad |year= 2003| ISBN= 978-1-853-72723-8 |pages= iv-v |url=http://books.google.com/books?id=PiCFgkGcxRQC&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false }}</ref> Mirza Ghulam Ahmad declared himself to be the [[Second Coming|second coming]] of Jesus for the Christians and the [[Mujaddid]] (renewer of faith) for the Muslims.<ref name="WebsterAhmad" /><ref name=Melton55>{{cite book|title=Religions of the World: A Comprehensive Encyclopedia of Beliefs and Practices| edition=2| isbn= 978-1-59884-203-6| publisher= ABC-CLIO |page= 55}}</ref>

=== Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED> views ===
In the teachings of the [[Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED> Faith]], Jesus is considered to be a [[Manifestation of God]], a concept in the Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED> Faith that refers to what are commonly called [[prophet]]s.<ref name="stockman">{{cite journal | title = Jesus Christ in the Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED> Writings | first = Robert | last = Stockman | journal = Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED> Studies Review | volume = 2 | issue = 1 | location = London | publisher =Association for Baha'i Studies English-Speaking Europe | year = 1992 | url = http://bahai-library.com/stockman_jesus_bahai_writings}}</ref> In Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED> thought, Manifestations of God are the intermediary between God and humanity, serving as messengers and reflecting God's qualities and attributes.<ref name="manifestation"/> The Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED> concept also emphasizes the simultaneously existing qualities of humanity and divinity. In the station of divinity, they show forth the will, knowledge and attributes of God; in the station of humanity, they show the physical qualities of common man.<ref name="manifestation"/>  This concept is most similar to the Christian concept of incarnation.<ref name="stockman"/> In Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED> thought, Jesus incarnated God's attributes as they were perfectly reflected and expressed, however Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED> teachings reject the Christian belief that Divinity was contained with a single human body because the Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED> teachings state that the essence of God is transcendent above the physical reality.<ref name="stockman"/>

[[Bah<U+00E1>'u'll<U+00E1>h]], the founder of the Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED> Faith, wrote that since each Manifestation of God has the same divine attributes they can be seen as the spiritual "return" of all the previous Manifestations of God, and the appearance of each new Manifestation of God inaugurates a religion that supersedes the former ones, a sequence known as [[Progressive revelation (Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED>)|progressive revelation]].<ref name="manifestation"/> Through this process Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED>'s believe God's plan unfolds gradually as mankind matures and some of the Manifestations arrive in specific fulfillment of the missions of previous ones. Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED>'s believe that in this sense, Bah<U+00E1>'u'll<U+00E1>h is the promised return of Christ.<ref name="psmith128">{{cite book |last = Smith |first = Peter |year = 2008 |title = An Introduction to the Baha'i Faith |publisher = Cambridge University Press |place = Cambridge
|url = http://books.google.com/?id=z7zdDFTzNr0C |isbn = 0-521-86251-5 | page = 128}}</ref>

Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED> teachings confirm many, but not all, aspects of the historical Jesus as portrayed in the Gospels. They believe in the Virgin Birth,<ref name=Lepart118>{{cite book | title = In the Glory of the Father: The Bahai Faith and Christianity | first = Brian D. | last = Lepard  | year = 2008 | publisher = Bahai Publishing | isbn = 1-931847-34-7 | page = 118}}</ref> and the crucifixion, but see the resurrection and the miracles he performed as symbolic.<ref name="Smith-jesus">{{cite book |last= Smith |first= Peter |work= A concise encyclopedia of the Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED> Faith |title= peace |year= 2000 |publisher=Oneworld Publications |location= Oxford |isbn= 1-85168-184-1 |page= 214}}</ref> Bah<U+00E1>'<U+00ED> thought also accepts Jesus' Sonship.<ref name="Smith-jesus"/>

===Buddhist views===
{{main|Buddhism and Christianity}}
[[Buddhist]] views of Jesus differ. Some [[Buddhism and Christianity|Buddhist views on Jesus]] including [[Tenzin Gyatso, 14th Dalai Lama|Tenzin Gyatso, the 14th Dalai Lama]]<ref>{{cite web|last=Beverley|first= James A.|url= http://www.christianitytoday.com/ct/2001/june11/15.64.html Hollywood's Idol|publisher= Christianity Today|title=Jesus Christ also lived previous lives| quote= So, you see, he reached a high state, either as a Bodhisattva, or an enlightened person, through Buddhist practice or something like that.| accessdate= 2007-04-20}}</ref> regard Jesus as a [[bodhisattva]] who dedicated his life to the welfare of human beings. It was recorded in [[101 Zen Stories]] that the 14th century Zen master [[Gasan J<U+014D>seki]], on hearing some of the sayings of Jesus in the Gospels, remarked that he was "an enlightened man", and "not far from Buddhahood".<ref>{{cite book|title=Zen Flesh Zen Bones: A Collection of Zen and Pre-Zen Writings|year=1998|publisher=Tuttle Publishing|isbn=978-0-8048-3186-4|editors=[[Nyogen Senzaki]] and Paul Reps|chapter=Story 16: Not far from Buddhahood|chapterurl=http://www.101zenstories.com/index.php?story=16|url=http://books.google.com.au/books?id=m9CCTo258n8C&lpg=PP1&dq=isbn%3A9780804831864&pg=PA6#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=2011-12-09|page=36}}</ref> On the other hand, Buddhist scholars such as [[Masao Abe]] and [[D. T. Suzuki]] have stated that the centrality of the crucifixion of Jesus to the Christian view of his life is totally irreconcilable with the foundations of Buddhism.<ref>{{cite book|title=Buddhism and Interfaith Dialogue|first1= Masao |last1=Abe |first2= Steven|last2= Heine|year= 1995| pages= 99<U+2013>100}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Mysticism, Christian and Buddhist|first= Daisetz T.|last= Suzuki |year= 2002| isbn= 1-60506-132-8| page= 113}}</ref>{{sfn|Houlden|2006|pp=140<U+2013>144}}

In a letter to his daughter [[Indira Gandhi]], [[Jawaharlal Nehru]] wrote, "All over Central Asia, in Kashmir and Ladakh and Tibet and even farther north, there is a strong belief that Jesus or Isa traveled about there."<ref>{{cite book|author=Jawarharlal Nehru|title=Glimpses of World History|location=New York|publisher=John Day Co.|year=1942|page=84}}</ref> The theory that an adult Jesus [[unknown years of Jesus|traveled to India]] first appeared in 1887 and generated other stories, but the author later confessed to fabricating it.<ref>Ehrman says "one of the most widely disseminated modern forgeries is called ''The Unknown Life of Jesus Christ''."({{harvnb|Ehrman|2011|p=252}})
*{{cite book|title=New Testament Apocrypha, Vol. 1: Gospels and Related Writings|first1=Wilhelm |last1=Schneemelcher |first2=R. M.|last2= Wilson|year=1990|ISBN= 066422721X |page= 84|quote= ...a particular book by Nicolas Notovich (Di Lucke im Leben Jesus 1894) ... shortly after the publication of the book, the reports of travel experiences were already unmasked as lies. The fantasies about Jesus in India were also soon recognized as invention... down to today, nobody has had a glimpse of the manuscripts with the alleged narratives about Jesus}}
*{{cite book|title=Indology, Indomania, and Orientalism|first= Douglas T.|last= McGetchin|year= 2010|publisher= Fairleigh Dickinson University Press |ISBN= 083864208X |page= 133| quote=Faced with this cross-examination, Notovich confessed to fabricating his evidence.}}</ref> [[Robert Van Voorst]] states that modern scholarship has "almost unanimously agreed" that claims of the travels of Jesus to Tibet, Kashmir or India contain "nothing of value".{{sfn|Van Voorst|2000|p=17}} [[Marcus Borg]] states that the suggestions that an adult Jesus traveled to Egypt or India and came into contact with Buddhism are "without historical foundation".<ref name=Dunn303/> Although modern parallels between the teachings of Jesus and Buddha have been drawn, these comparisons emerged after missionary contacts in the 19th century, and there is no historically reliable evidence of contacts between Buddhism and Jesus during his life.{{sfn|Houlden|2006|p=140}} [[John Dominic Crossan]] states that none of the theories presented to fill the 15<U+2013>18 year gap between the early life of Jesus and the start of [[Ministry of Jesus|his ministry]] have been supported by modern scholarship.{{sfn|Crossan|Watts|1999|pp=28-29}}

===Other views===
{{see also|Criticism of Jesus}}
[[Manichaeism]] (which at one point included [[Augustine of Hippo]] as a follower, who later opposed it) accepted Jesus as a prophet, along with [[Gautama Buddha]] and [[Zoroaster]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Bevan|first=A. A.|year=1930|title=Manichaeism|work=[[Encyclopaedia of Religion and Ethics]]|volume=8|editor=[[James Hastings]]|location=London}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Augustine of Hippo: A Biography| first= Peter R. L.|last= Brown|year= 2000| isbn= 0-520-22757-3| page =43}}</ref> More recently, the [[New Age]] movement entertains a wide variety of views on Jesus. The New Age movement generally teaches that [[Initiation (Theosophy)|Christhood]] is something that all may attain. [[Theosophy|Theosophists]], from whom many New Age teachings originated, refer to Jesus as the [[Master Jesus]] and believe the Christ, after various [[reincarnation|incarnations]] occupied the body of Jesus.<ref>{{cite book|title=A Treatise on Cosmic Fire|first1=Alice|last1=Bailey|first2=Djwhal|last2=Khul|isbn=978-0-85330-117-2|publisher=Lucis Publishing Company|page=1193|year=2005|origyear=1932}}</ref> U.S. President [[Thomas Jefferson]], a [[deism|deist]], created the [[Jefferson Bible]], an early (but not complete) [[gospel harmony]] that included only Jesus' ethical teachings because he did not believe in Jesus' divinity or any of the other supernatural aspects of the Bible.<ref>{{cite journal | first = Erik | last = Reece | url = http://www.harpers.org/archive/2005/12/0080847 | title = Jesus Without The Miracles <U+2013> Thomas Jefferson's Bible and the Gospel of Thomas | magazine =Harper's Magazine | volume=311 | month=Dec| year=2005 | issue=1867 | pages = 33<U+2013>41| archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/63nm56xLe|archivedate=2011-12-09}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=''Tradition and incarnation: foundations of Christian theology|first=William L.|last= Portier |year=1993| isbn= 0-8091-3467-5| page= 218}}</ref>

Critics of Jesus included [[Celsus]] in the 2nd century and [[Porphyry (philosopher)|Porphyry]] who wrote a 15-volume attack on Christianity as a whole.<ref>{{cite book|editor-last=Chadwick|editor-first= Henry|author= Origen |title=Contra Celsum| publisher=Cambridge University Press |year=1980| page= xxviii| url=http://books.google.com/books?id=wsKLIV3TpOYC&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|first=J.|last= Stevenson |title= A New Eusebius: Documents illustrating the history of the Church to AD 337|year=1987|editor-first= W. H. C.|editor-last= Frend| page= 257| isbn= 0-281-04268-3}}</ref> Criticism of Jesus continued into the 19th century, with [[Nietzsche]] being highly critical of Jesus. For instance, Nietzsche considered Jesus' teachings anti-natural in their treatment of topics such as sexuality.<ref>{{cite book|first=Friedrich |last=Nietzsche|year= 1895|title= Twilight of the Idols, Morality as Anti-nature}}</ref> In the 20th century [[Bertrand Russell]] was also critical of Jesus and in ''[[Why I Am Not a Christian]]'' stated that Jesus was "not so wise as some other people have been, and He was certainly not superlatively wise."<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|last=Russell|first= Bertrand|title= Why I am not a Christian| encyclopedia = Why I am Not a Christian: And Other Essays on Religion and Related Subjects|year= 2004| publisher =Routledge Classics| page= 13}}</ref>

